00:00:02.070 --> 00:00:05.390
Prof: Hi,
this is John Geanakoplos again.

00:00:05.390 --> 00:00:08.795
Here to give a lecture,
that I gave one evening,

00:00:08.795 --> 00:00:10.680
that we couldn't record.
 

00:00:10.680 --> 00:00:12.955
So I'm going to try and
reproduce the lecture as

00:00:12.955 --> 00:00:14.020
faithfully as I can.
 

00:00:14.020 --> 00:00:17.860
And I think it's a historical
lecture.

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:19.090
I hope you find it interesting.
 

00:00:19.090 --> 00:00:21.750
It's about the history of the
mortgage market.

00:00:21.750 --> 00:00:24.822
And I call it a personal
history because by some

00:00:24.822 --> 00:00:28.941
accident, I participated at many
of the key points in the recent

00:00:28.941 --> 00:00:31.230
history of the mortgage market.
 

00:00:31.230 --> 00:00:35.040
So I started off in 1989.
 

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:37.280
I was professor here at Yale.
 

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:39.430
I was a mathematical economist.
 

00:00:39.430 --> 00:00:43.849
I thought of myself as using
mathematics to study economics

00:00:43.849 --> 00:00:48.497
and staying really pretty much
as far from the real world as I

00:00:48.497 --> 00:00:49.260
could.
 

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:51.948
But for some reason,
I decided that I wanted to see

00:00:51.948 --> 00:00:53.830
what was going on on Wall
Street.

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:57.092
The most interesting
mathematical modeling of that

00:00:57.092 --> 00:00:59.490
day was being done on Wall
Street.

00:00:59.490 --> 00:01:02.570
And mathematical modeling and
finance, that is in economics.

00:01:02.570 --> 00:01:03.350
And so I decided.
 

00:01:03.350 --> 00:01:04.578
why not go see it?
 

00:01:04.578 --> 00:01:08.938
And so I visited a bunch of
investment banks.

00:01:08.938 --> 00:01:12.210
A number of my friends,
including one from Yale,

00:01:12.210 --> 00:01:14.299
had worked at Goldman Sachs.
 

00:01:14.299 --> 00:01:15.989
So that was the natural thing
to do.

00:01:15.989 --> 00:01:21.480
But, I had a little cousin who
had just been hired recently,

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:24.200
a little bit before that,
at Kidder Peabody,

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:27.784
which was sort of the number
seventh investment bank at the

00:01:27.784 --> 00:01:29.610
time,
in terms of size.

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:33.754
And he introduced me to the
fellow, Ed Cerullo,

00:01:33.754 --> 00:01:36.910
who ran fixed income at the
time.

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:39.224
And they persuaded me that it
would be much more interesting

00:01:39.224 --> 00:01:41.524
to go to Kidder,
Peabody and to talk to people

00:01:41.524 --> 00:01:44.426
like Ed Cerullo,
than go to Goldman Sachs and be

00:01:44.426 --> 00:01:46.800
one of a hundred visiting
professors.

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:48.724
So I decided that the firm was
a little bit smaller,

00:01:48.724 --> 00:01:49.819
but I would see more of it.
 

00:01:49.819 --> 00:01:51.970
And why not do something a
little bit different?

00:01:51.970 --> 00:01:54.169
So they never had an academic
visitor, I think,

00:01:54.169 --> 00:01:55.890
like me spend a year there
before.

00:01:55.890 --> 00:01:59.550
So I went in 1989 to 1990.
 

00:01:59.550 --> 00:02:02.769
And while I was there I talked
a lot to Ed Cerullo and to the

00:02:02.769 --> 00:02:04.968
traders and to a bunch of other
people.

00:02:04.968 --> 00:02:08.550
And at the end of the my
sabbatical,

00:02:08.550 --> 00:02:11.445
Ed Cerullo came to me and he
said, you know I've come to

00:02:11.445 --> 00:02:14.554
realize that our fixed income
research department isn't very

00:02:14.554 --> 00:02:15.449
mathematical.
 

00:02:15.449 --> 00:02:19.300
Why don't you hire a research
department for me?

00:02:19.300 --> 00:02:20.598
And I'll help you along.
 

00:02:20.598 --> 00:02:22.818
But, you find the people,
you know the subject,

00:02:22.818 --> 00:02:25.818
you can judge,
your business is judging people

00:02:25.818 --> 00:02:28.363
doing research,
why don't you hire me a

00:02:28.363 --> 00:02:29.590
research department?
 

00:02:29.590 --> 00:02:32.995
So I hired him a research
department, which ultimately

00:02:32.995 --> 00:02:34.280
grew to 75 people.
 

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:36.878
And I returned to Yale.
 

00:02:36.878 --> 00:02:39.400
And after I got back to Yale,
he called me up and he said,

00:02:39.400 --> 00:02:41.440
now that you've hired the
research department,

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:43.160
you have heads of all these
different groups,

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:45.449
why don't you run the research
department?

00:02:45.449 --> 00:02:49.508
You can do it from Yale,
as a consultant.

00:02:49.508 --> 00:02:53.360
And so I became the head of
fixed income research at Kidder

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:54.690
Peabody from Yale.
 

00:02:54.690 --> 00:02:57.258
And it was quite an experience.
 

00:02:57.258 --> 00:03:00.098
I hadn't realized,
when I accepted the job,

00:03:00.098 --> 00:03:02.938
just how many complications
would arise.

00:03:02.938 --> 00:03:05.399
How many people would get job
offers from other places and

00:03:05.399 --> 00:03:06.090
want to leave.
 

00:03:06.090 --> 00:03:08.288
And how many models wouldn't
work.

00:03:08.288 --> 00:03:11.008
And then there'd have to be a
wild scramble to fix it.

00:03:11.008 --> 00:03:14.217
But anyway, that placed me at
an investment bank,

00:03:14.217 --> 00:03:17.894
that would become one of the
key players in the mortgage

00:03:17.894 --> 00:03:18.628
market.
 

00:03:18.628 --> 00:03:20.490
Now in the mortgage market,
well who are the players?

00:03:20.490 --> 00:03:22.639
They are the homeowners you all
know about.

00:03:22.639 --> 00:03:25.598
They are the banks who are
giving mortgage loans.

00:03:25.598 --> 00:03:28.829
But then there are a number of
other players that are invisible

00:03:28.829 --> 00:03:31.276
to much of the public,
which really dominate the

00:03:31.276 --> 00:03:31.848
market.
 

00:03:31.848 --> 00:03:34.247
There's the government
agencies, Fannie Mae and Freddie

00:03:34.247 --> 00:03:35.889
Mac, which you'll hear a lot
about.

00:03:35.889 --> 00:03:38.895
There are the investment banks,
like Kidder Peabody and Goldman

00:03:38.895 --> 00:03:40.348
Sachs and a bunch of others.
 

00:03:40.348 --> 00:03:43.848
There are the hedge funds and
there are other investors.

00:03:43.848 --> 00:03:48.449
And this group of people
creates a gigantic hierarchy,

00:03:48.449 --> 00:03:52.268
an invisible market,
that's on the same size,

00:03:52.268 --> 00:03:55.740
the same scale,
as the stock market.

00:03:55.740 --> 00:03:58.865
So I think in that time,
1989,1990, if you'd asked

00:03:58.865 --> 00:04:02.627
anyone in America practically,
what's an important financial

00:04:02.627 --> 00:04:03.330
market?
 

00:04:03.330 --> 00:04:05.218
They would have said,
the stock market.

00:04:05.218 --> 00:04:07.419
What's another important
financial market?

00:04:07.419 --> 00:04:08.810
Corporate bond market.
 

00:04:08.810 --> 00:04:09.849
What's another one?
 

00:04:09.849 --> 00:04:14.509
Well, foreign exchange market.
 

00:04:14.509 --> 00:04:15.319
What's another one?
 

00:04:15.319 --> 00:04:16.759
Options market.
 

00:04:16.759 --> 00:04:20.449
I don't think anyone would have
said the mortgage market.

00:04:20.449 --> 00:04:24.754
Or at least they wouldn't have
said it very early on in their

00:04:24.754 --> 00:04:27.480
list of important financial
markets.

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:29.497
But in fact,
as I'm going to try and tell

00:04:29.497 --> 00:04:32.509
you during this class,
the mortgage market is not only

00:04:32.509 --> 00:04:34.769
on the same scale as the stock
market,

00:04:34.769 --> 00:04:37.408
but actually quite a bit more
complicated than the stock

00:04:37.408 --> 00:04:37.839
market.
 

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:39.709
More mathematical than the
stock market.

00:04:39.709 --> 00:04:42.016
And in some ways,
more interesting than the stock

00:04:42.016 --> 00:04:42.449
market.
 

00:04:42.449 --> 00:04:45.091
And as we'll see at the end of
the course, it was the mortgage

00:04:45.091 --> 00:04:47.560
market that led to the greatest
crisis we've had since the

00:04:47.560 --> 00:04:48.209
depression.
 

00:04:48.209 --> 00:04:51.146
And in fact,
caused several similar crises

00:04:51.146 --> 00:04:52.149
before that.
 

00:04:52.149 --> 00:04:56.420
So mortgages appear at the
bottom.

00:04:56.420 --> 00:05:00.430
You have homeowners living in
their houses who need to borrow

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:02.370
the money to buy the house.
 

00:05:02.370 --> 00:05:04.713
Before they can live in the
house they have to get the money

00:05:04.713 --> 00:05:05.470
to buy the house.
 

00:05:05.470 --> 00:05:07.680
So they borrow the money by
taking out a mortgage.

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:10.886
And it's a bank or a thrift or
somebody like that who lends the

00:05:10.886 --> 00:05:11.300
money.
 

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:13.420
That's the first step.
 

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:18.074
So a mortgage is just a promise
to pay the loan back over a long

00:05:18.074 --> 00:05:21.620
period of time using your house
as collateral.

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:24.663
An important part of mortgages
is that you have an option to

00:05:24.663 --> 00:05:25.850
pre pay the mortgage.
 

00:05:25.850 --> 00:05:27.610
I mean, what if you move?
 

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:29.778
The mortgage is,
say, a 30-year promise.

00:05:29.778 --> 00:05:31.790
And after three years,
you might want to move.

00:05:31.790 --> 00:05:34.345
So, if you're gone from the
house, the house can no longer

00:05:34.345 --> 00:05:36.990
serve as collateral because you
don't live in it anymore.

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:39.620
So there has to be some way of
getting out of the mortgage.

00:05:39.620 --> 00:05:41.899
And so there's an option to pre
pay it.

00:05:41.899 --> 00:05:45.002
Now, in the United States,
that option can be used even if

00:05:45.002 --> 00:05:46.310
you stay in the house.
 

00:05:46.310 --> 00:05:50.336
And it turns out to be one of
the more problematic aspects of

00:05:50.336 --> 00:05:51.680
valuing mortgages.
 

00:05:51.680 --> 00:05:54.370
And one of the most interesting
aspects of valuing mortgages.

00:05:54.370 --> 00:05:56.060
We'll come to that later.
 

00:05:56.060 --> 00:05:59.153
So this idea of a mortgage,
those three ideas,

00:05:59.153 --> 00:06:02.726
were already known to the
Babylonians more than 3,000

00:06:02.726 --> 00:06:03.689
years ago.
 

00:06:03.689 --> 00:06:05.790
So the mortgage is not a recent
invention.

00:06:05.790 --> 00:06:10.528
It wasn't invented after the
industrial revolution.

00:06:10.528 --> 00:06:15.100
It was invented more than 3,000
years ago near the Middle East.

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:19.507
So, it's stayed pretty much the
same for most of those 3,000

00:06:19.507 --> 00:06:23.468
years until the 1930s when the
amortizing mortgage was

00:06:23.468 --> 00:06:24.439
invented.
 

00:06:24.439 --> 00:06:28.120
So what happened in the 1930s,
that was the time of the Great

00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:32.230
Depression and farmers had lots
of mortgages and they would owe,

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:35.069
$7.00 a year,
say, as their interest payment.

00:06:35.069 --> 00:06:38.661
And at the end of 10 or 15
years, they'd have to pay $107,

00:06:38.661 --> 00:06:41.370
that is they make their
interest payment.

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:43.379
And they pay back the balance.
 

00:06:43.379 --> 00:06:44.910
What's called now a balloon
payment.

00:06:44.910 --> 00:06:46.959
That's how a typical bond works.
 

00:06:46.959 --> 00:06:50.583
Well, of course when things got
really bad, a lot of them

00:06:50.583 --> 00:06:51.360
defaulted.
 

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:54.026
And naturally,
they chose to default just

00:06:54.026 --> 00:06:55.759
before the $107 payment.
 

00:06:55.759 --> 00:06:59.146
So seeing that,
mortgage lenders decided that

00:06:59.146 --> 00:07:03.762
it would be much safer to make a
flat mortgage loan where the

00:07:03.762 --> 00:07:07.730
payment was say,
$8.00 a year for all of thirty

00:07:07.730 --> 00:07:08.278
years.
 

00:07:08.278 --> 00:07:10.841
Now, you pay a little bit more
each year for 29 years,

00:07:10.841 --> 00:07:13.500
but then you continue to pay
the $8.00 the 30th year.

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:15.326
But you see,
if you add up all the extra

00:07:15.326 --> 00:07:17.810
payments and you realize that
there's discounting,

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:21.055
the $107 way off in the end
isn't really that much money

00:07:21.055 --> 00:07:23.180
when looked at from the
beginning.

00:07:23.180 --> 00:07:27.072
And so by paying $8.00 every
year, you can get the same

00:07:27.072 --> 00:07:31.182
present discounted value of
paying $7.00 29 years and $107

00:07:31.182 --> 00:07:32.480
the 30th year.
 

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:34.000
So that's called the amortizing
mortgage.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.584
It makes the lender much safer
because after a bunch of years

00:07:37.584 --> 00:07:40.093
have gone by,
the house presumably has gone

00:07:40.093 --> 00:07:41.050
up in value.
 

00:07:41.050 --> 00:07:44.170
Or even if it hasn't gone up in
value, the remaining payments

00:07:44.170 --> 00:07:47.293
are much less because so many
have been made that the balance

00:07:47.293 --> 00:07:48.490
has been amortized.
 

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:51.435
And so actually to get out of
your mortgage,

00:07:51.435 --> 00:07:54.040
you need to pay less than $100
back.

00:07:54.040 --> 00:07:56.711
So this amortizing mortgage is
something we're going to study

00:07:56.711 --> 00:07:58.360
mathematically in the next
lecture.

00:07:58.360 --> 00:08:01.978
But now, I just mentioned that
was one of the big innovations,

00:08:01.978 --> 00:08:05.300
which made the mortgage market
much safer than before.

00:08:05.300 --> 00:08:09.502
Well so things continued pretty
much the same from the 1930s all

00:08:09.502 --> 00:08:12.838
the way to the 1970s when we had
securitization.

00:08:12.838 --> 00:08:15.834
Like many of the great
financial innovations in

00:08:15.834 --> 00:08:19.089
history, this one was created by
the government.

00:08:19.089 --> 00:08:24.035
So Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac
were government Agencies They

00:08:24.035 --> 00:08:26.850
were created by the government.
 

00:08:26.850 --> 00:08:30.370
They then became eventually
separate from the government.

00:08:30.370 --> 00:08:33.702
But they were given the task,
they were created for the

00:08:33.702 --> 00:08:36.419
purpose, of making mortgage
pass-throughs.

00:08:36.419 --> 00:08:38.168
So we're in the 1970s.
 

00:08:38.168 --> 00:08:42.077
So mortgage pass-throughs are
the second tier of this

00:08:42.077 --> 00:08:42.980
hierarchy.
 

00:08:42.980 --> 00:08:45.850
So the banks who had lent the
mortgage, remember when you take

00:08:45.850 --> 00:08:48.720
out a mortgage as a homeowner,
you're selling your promise.

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:51.124
You're getting the money by
selling your promise to pay back

00:08:51.124 --> 00:08:51.450
later.
 

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:53.769
So those promises are collected
by the banks.

00:08:53.769 --> 00:08:56.143
And instead of just sitting on
the promises,

00:08:56.143 --> 00:08:58.626
the banks now,
with Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac

00:08:58.626 --> 00:09:01.940
could sell their promises to
Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:05.413
And Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac
would put them together in

00:09:05.413 --> 00:09:08.080
gigantic pools called pass
through pools.

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:09.178
Why were they called
pass-throughs?

00:09:09.178 --> 00:09:12.711
Because the mortgage payments
the homeowners made would go to

00:09:12.711 --> 00:09:16.418
the banks and the banks would
just pass them on to the pools.

00:09:16.418 --> 00:09:20.090
And then the pools would
collect the money and pass that

00:09:20.090 --> 00:09:22.158
money on to the shareholders.
 

00:09:22.158 --> 00:09:26.250
So the ultimate lenders to the
homeowners are the people who

00:09:26.250 --> 00:09:29.370
buy shares in the Fannie and
Freddie pools.

00:09:29.370 --> 00:09:32.046
So the banks appear to the
homeowner to be lending the

00:09:32.046 --> 00:09:32.450
money.
 

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:33.710
But actually,
they're not lending it all.

00:09:33.710 --> 00:09:35.168
They are the middleman.
 

00:09:35.168 --> 00:09:38.527
And so they collect the money
from the homeowner and they send

00:09:38.527 --> 00:09:41.553
it on to the actual lender,
who's the shareholder of the

00:09:41.553 --> 00:09:42.048
pool.
 

00:09:42.048 --> 00:09:44.509
And the banks are also the
servicer, really.

00:09:44.509 --> 00:09:47.620
They're getting paid a fee for
collecting the money and writing

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:50.230
threatening letters if the
homeowner stops paying.

00:09:50.230 --> 00:09:52.846
And as we'll see later,
throwing the homeowner out of

00:09:52.846 --> 00:09:54.908
his house if the homeowner
doesn't pay.

00:09:54.908 --> 00:09:59.648
So Fannie and Freddie played an
extraordinarily important role

00:09:59.648 --> 00:10:01.590
in the mortgage market.
 

00:10:01.590 --> 00:10:03.794
First of all,
not any mortgage could be sold

00:10:03.794 --> 00:10:04.769
into these pools.
 

00:10:04.769 --> 00:10:07.519
They had to meet strict
criteria.

00:10:07.519 --> 00:10:08.870
You had to have a good credit
rating.

00:10:08.870 --> 00:10:10.710
You had to have a job.
 

00:10:10.710 --> 00:10:19.467
You had to have all sorts of--
sorry about this,

00:10:19.467 --> 00:10:28.038
I'm going to have to shut off
my cell phone.

00:10:28.038 --> 00:10:31.164
So the loan to value of the
mortgage had to be,

00:10:31.164 --> 00:10:35.309
that is if the house is worth
$100, the loan could only be 80%

00:10:35.309 --> 00:10:35.990
of it.
 

00:10:35.990 --> 00:10:41.690
You had to have a record of the
job you had and so on.

00:10:41.690 --> 00:10:51.370
So this was very standardized
and very high performing loans.

00:10:51.370 --> 00:10:54.345
You could contrast with,
say, to the world that you

00:10:54.345 --> 00:10:57.500
might have seen in the movie
It's a Wonderful Life.

00:10:57.500 --> 00:10:59.445
So in the movie It's a
Wonderful Life,

00:10:59.445 --> 00:11:02.653
you remember Jimmy Stewart runs
a thrift and he makes mortgage

00:11:02.653 --> 00:11:03.178
loans.
 

00:11:03.178 --> 00:11:05.320
And people come to him and they
say we want a loan.

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:08.528
And you know one guy comes and
says he wants a loan.

00:11:08.528 --> 00:11:10.966
Jimmy Stewart says,
well do you have any

00:11:10.966 --> 00:11:11.778
collateral?
 

00:11:11.778 --> 00:11:14.427
No, I haven't built the house
yet, you know I'm trying to

00:11:14.427 --> 00:11:15.278
build the house.
 

00:11:15.278 --> 00:11:18.149
Do you have a record of
employment?

00:11:18.149 --> 00:11:21.960
No, I just moved here,
I don't have a job yet.

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:24.580
Do you have someone who can
vouch for you?

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:25.490
No.
 

00:11:25.490 --> 00:11:27.320
Do you have a credit rating?
 

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:27.860
No.
 

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:29.840
There's no such thing as credit
rating.

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.966
So then Jimmy Stewart looks
into his eyes and realizes this

00:11:32.966 --> 00:11:35.500
is a good honest person and
gives him a loan.

00:11:35.500 --> 00:11:38.750
Well, that doesn't happen in
the Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac

00:11:38.750 --> 00:11:39.200
pools.
 

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:41.440
They're very standardized
criterion.

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:45.187
And that guy,
Martini who got the loan from

00:11:45.187 --> 00:11:50.450
Jimmy Stewart would never have
gotten a conforming Fannie or

00:11:50.450 --> 00:11:53.928
Freddie loan in the 1980s or
1990s.

00:11:53.928 --> 00:11:56.030
Might have gotten one in the
2000s though,

00:11:56.030 --> 00:11:57.570
but we'll come back to that.
 

00:11:57.570 --> 00:12:01.745
So that kind of market is very
much like the kind of market in

00:12:01.745 --> 00:12:04.895
the Jimmy Stewart movie,
It's a Wonderful Life,

00:12:04.895 --> 00:12:07.428
that gets created in his
fantasy.

00:12:07.428 --> 00:12:09.864
Where you know,
the town gets taken over by the

00:12:09.864 --> 00:12:11.769
evil banker and that evil
banker,

00:12:11.769 --> 00:12:14.129
whose name I've forgotten at
the moment,

00:12:14.129 --> 00:12:17.408
but that evil banker basically
is creating the kind of loans,

00:12:17.408 --> 00:12:19.408
almost, that we're talking
about now.

00:12:19.408 --> 00:12:21.580
Everything's mechanized and
standardized.

00:12:21.580 --> 00:12:25.389
Of course with standardization
you get tremendous advantages.

00:12:25.389 --> 00:12:29.716
For one thing,
these loans being pooled

00:12:29.716 --> 00:12:35.980
together and being of the same
general good quality,

00:12:35.980 --> 00:12:38.818
they allow the lenders,
instead of lending to a bunch

00:12:38.818 --> 00:12:41.548
of homeowners in Peoria like the
bank would do,

00:12:41.548 --> 00:12:44.519
now all those Peoria loans are
stuck with a bunch of other

00:12:44.519 --> 00:12:47.750
loans from all over the country
in the same big Fannie pool.

00:12:47.750 --> 00:12:49.871
And so the lenders,
who are the shareholders,

00:12:49.871 --> 00:12:51.320
have diversified their risk.
 

00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:53.950
If the big businesses in
Peoria, Illinois go under,

00:12:53.950 --> 00:12:56.528
it might be that all the
homeowners in Peoria will

00:12:56.528 --> 00:12:58.158
default on their mortgages.
 

00:12:58.158 --> 00:13:00.160
But not in the Fannie and
Freddie pools,

00:13:00.160 --> 00:13:02.830
because those are loans from
all over the country.

00:13:02.830 --> 00:13:06.186
So it would have to be that
businesses all over the country

00:13:06.186 --> 00:13:08.558
went bad for those loans all to
go bad.

00:13:08.558 --> 00:13:10.857
So secondly,
if you're getting a whole pool

00:13:10.857 --> 00:13:13.812
and there's an automatic
criterion for getting into the

00:13:13.812 --> 00:13:15.532
pool,
you don't have to worry that

00:13:15.532 --> 00:13:17.835
you're getting the worst loans
or the cheatiest loans or

00:13:17.835 --> 00:13:18.379
something.
 

00:13:18.379 --> 00:13:20.285
You know the quality,
the general quality,

00:13:20.285 --> 00:13:21.168
of all the loans.
 

00:13:21.168 --> 00:13:26.360
And once you have shares in a
pool, you can resell the shares.

00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:29.932
So a bank who has to study the
homeowner and you know have

00:13:29.932 --> 00:13:31.250
meetings with them.
 

00:13:31.250 --> 00:13:32.985
And you know,
Jimmy Stewart had to look into

00:13:32.985 --> 00:13:33.428
his eyes.
 

00:13:33.428 --> 00:13:35.958
So Jimmy Stewart may have
convinced himself the guy is a

00:13:35.958 --> 00:13:38.672
good risk, but how could Jimmy
Stewart ever sell the loan to

00:13:38.672 --> 00:13:39.500
somebody else.
 

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:41.174
The other buyer,
who hasn't looked into

00:13:41.174 --> 00:13:43.027
Martini's eyes,
he's never going to believe

00:13:43.027 --> 00:13:44.879
Jimmy Stewart that that's a good
loan.

00:13:44.879 --> 00:13:47.559
So Jimmy Stewart is going to be
stuck with that loan for 30

00:13:47.559 --> 00:13:47.928
years.
 

00:13:47.928 --> 00:13:50.947
In the Fannie and Freddie
pools, the shareholder who buys

00:13:50.947 --> 00:13:54.018
the loans and knows they're
standardized knows exactly the

00:13:54.018 --> 00:13:57.519
same thing as the next guy who
might buy his shares from him.

00:13:57.519 --> 00:14:00.363
So if the shareholder will be
willing to pay more for the

00:14:00.363 --> 00:14:02.274
loan,
because he knows that if he

00:14:02.274 --> 00:14:04.256
needs cash,
he doesn't have to wait 30

00:14:04.256 --> 00:14:06.820
years, he can just sell his
shares to somebody else.

00:14:06.820 --> 00:14:08.678
So because of the
diversification,

00:14:08.678 --> 00:14:10.970
because of the reduction in
adverse selection,

00:14:10.970 --> 00:14:13.389
and because of this ability to
resell the shares,

00:14:13.389 --> 00:14:16.816
lenders, that is shareholders,
are willing to pay more for the

00:14:16.816 --> 00:14:17.490
mortgages.
 

00:14:17.490 --> 00:14:19.408
And so the mortgage rate went
down.

00:14:19.408 --> 00:14:23.421
So, I've estimated that this
operation together with the next

00:14:23.421 --> 00:14:27.231
one I'm going to talk about,
has reduced mortgage rates by

00:14:27.231 --> 00:14:28.769
at least a percent.
 

00:14:28.769 --> 00:14:31.634
So if you think the average
loan is $200,000,

00:14:31.634 --> 00:14:35.605
you're talking about $2,000 a
year that the average homeowners

00:14:35.605 --> 00:14:38.080
save by this financial
innovation.

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:42.048
So securitization seems to have
been a great boon.

00:14:42.048 --> 00:14:43.976
Now in 2002,
when I made these slides,

00:14:43.976 --> 00:14:47.308
I'll just give you an idea of
the size of the mortgage market.

00:14:47.308 --> 00:14:49.808
And you have to double all
these numbers today,

00:14:49.808 --> 00:14:50.570
pretty much.
 

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:54.056
So you see that you know the
stock market was around $15

00:14:54.056 --> 00:14:57.860
trillion and the mortgages
around $7 trillion at the time.

00:14:57.860 --> 00:15:02.000
And you know that compares to
$2 trillion for corporate bonds

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.210
or $3 trillion for treasuries.
 

00:15:04.210 --> 00:15:06.207
You see how big the mortgage
market was then,

00:15:06.207 --> 00:15:07.480
and now it's twice as big.
 

00:15:07.480 --> 00:15:10.943
It's the same size basically as
the stock market,

00:15:10.943 --> 00:15:13.759
which hasn't really grown since
then.

00:15:13.759 --> 00:15:18.730
So, I don't have time to talk
about this.

00:15:18.730 --> 00:15:20.952
But, of course,
of the mortgage market,

00:15:20.952 --> 00:15:24.110
some of it is commercial,
some of it is residential.

00:15:24.110 --> 00:15:25.590
The vast majority is
residential.

00:15:25.590 --> 00:15:27.700
But there's a very big
commercial mortgage market.

00:15:27.700 --> 00:15:31.794
I'm going to be talking mostly
about the residential mortgage

00:15:31.794 --> 00:15:32.408
market.
 

00:15:32.408 --> 00:15:35.970
Some of these mortgages are in
fact held by the banks without

00:15:35.970 --> 00:15:38.639
selling them to Fannie Mae and
Freddie Mac.

00:15:38.639 --> 00:15:41.591
But a lot of them are
securitized just in the way we

00:15:41.591 --> 00:15:42.460
talked about.
 

00:15:42.460 --> 00:15:44.921
And they're going to be private
securitizations later that we'll

00:15:44.921 --> 00:15:45.428
talk about.
 

00:15:45.428 --> 00:15:52.029
And so now that securitized
part is $10 trillion.

00:15:52.029 --> 00:15:56.470
I'll give the numbers,
recent numbers,

00:15:56.470 --> 00:15:57.428
later.
 

00:15:57.428 --> 00:15:59.570
So actually that may be a
little bit big.

00:15:59.570 --> 00:16:02.783
The $7 trillion,
the securitized part of the

00:16:02.783 --> 00:16:04.129
mortgage market.
 

00:16:04.129 --> 00:16:11.678
So in 2002, the agencies
dominated the security market.

00:16:11.678 --> 00:16:15.124
The securitized loans were
almost all Fannie Mae and

00:16:15.124 --> 00:16:16.070
Freddie Mac.
 

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:19.046
There's also another agency
called Ginnie Mae,

00:16:19.046 --> 00:16:22.950
but there was another part of
it, which were jumbo loans.

00:16:22.950 --> 00:16:24.149
So there was a size limit.
 

00:16:24.149 --> 00:16:26.519
The loans couldn't be too small
and couldn't be too big for

00:16:26.519 --> 00:16:27.870
these Fannie and Freddie pools.
 

00:16:27.870 --> 00:16:32.090
The government was trying to
appeal to the middle class.

00:16:32.090 --> 00:16:35.570
Establish homeownership in the
reliable middle class.

00:16:35.570 --> 00:16:39.148
And so the wealthy who were
buying million dollar homes

00:16:39.148 --> 00:16:43.123
weren't able to get their loans
sold into a Fannie or Freddie

00:16:43.123 --> 00:16:43.720
pool.
 

00:16:43.720 --> 00:16:47.289
And so those loans were
securitized the same way,

00:16:47.289 --> 00:16:51.827
but by private agencies and not
by banks, by investment banks,

00:16:51.827 --> 00:16:54.058
and not by the government.
 

00:16:54.058 --> 00:16:56.259
And that at the time,
in 2002, was half a trillion.

00:16:56.259 --> 00:16:59.669
We'll come to all these numbers
later.

00:16:59.669 --> 00:17:01.288
When we say today's numbers.
 

00:17:01.288 --> 00:17:04.712
So the next innovation after
the 1970s, came in the 80s and

00:17:04.712 --> 00:17:07.960
that's the collateralized
mortgage obligation market.

00:17:07.960 --> 00:17:09.660
CMOs, they are called.
 

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:13.444
So the investment banks like
Kidder Peabody and Lehman

00:17:13.444 --> 00:17:16.944
Brothers, for example,
would buy some of these big

00:17:16.944 --> 00:17:17.660
pools.
 

00:17:17.660 --> 00:17:20.598
And then they would cut the
pools, which were just

00:17:20.598 --> 00:17:21.558
pass-throughs.
 

00:17:21.558 --> 00:17:24.308
So the pools just passed
through the money that the

00:17:24.308 --> 00:17:25.960
homeowners were giving them.
 

00:17:25.960 --> 00:17:29.106
So maybe they were passing
through $1,000 a month as the

00:17:29.106 --> 00:17:29.680
promise.
 

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:34.292
Well, say Kidder Peabody,
might buy a pool promising

00:17:34.292 --> 00:17:37.640
$1,000 a month to the
shareholders.

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:40.058
And then cut the promise into
two pieces.

00:17:40.058 --> 00:17:42.877
Maybe a floater,
which would pay $500 plus the

00:17:42.877 --> 00:17:43.880
interest rate.
 

00:17:43.880 --> 00:17:47.076
And so when the interest rate
went up, the payments would go

00:17:47.076 --> 00:17:49.190
up, that's why it's called a
floater.

00:17:49.190 --> 00:17:51.705
And maybe a second piece called
an inverse floater,

00:17:51.705 --> 00:17:53.720
which is $500 minus the
interest rate.

00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:56.089
So as the interest rate went
up, the payments would get

00:17:56.089 --> 00:17:56.529
smaller.
 

00:17:56.529 --> 00:17:58.618
But as the interest rate went
down, the payments would get

00:17:58.618 --> 00:17:58.950
bigger.
 

00:17:58.950 --> 00:18:00.278
That's called an inverse
floater.

00:18:00.278 --> 00:18:02.519
So that way the two add up to
$1,000.

00:18:02.519 --> 00:18:05.990
But now, you can appeal to two
different buyers.

00:18:05.990 --> 00:18:09.041
A buyer who needs the money
when interest rates go up would

00:18:09.041 --> 00:18:09.990
buy the floater.
 

00:18:09.990 --> 00:18:12.411
A buyer who needs the money
when interest rates go down,

00:18:12.411 --> 00:18:13.818
would buy the inverse floater.
 

00:18:13.818 --> 00:18:17.210
So by creating out of plain
vanilla promise,

00:18:17.210 --> 00:18:21.625
two more tailored promises,
you can target more sharply a

00:18:21.625 --> 00:18:22.730
clientele.
 

00:18:22.730 --> 00:18:26.009
And therefore get probably more
than half the money for each of

00:18:26.009 --> 00:18:26.910
the two pieces.
 

00:18:26.910 --> 00:18:29.615
And that way,
of course competition in the

00:18:29.615 --> 00:18:33.376
CMO market raises the amount
people are willing to pay for

00:18:33.376 --> 00:18:34.828
the pass-throughs.
 

00:18:34.828 --> 00:18:37.559
Because they can then buy them
and split them up.

00:18:37.559 --> 00:18:40.190
And sell them for more.
 

00:18:40.190 --> 00:18:42.098
So that raises the price of the
pass-throughs,

00:18:42.098 --> 00:18:44.923
which in turn raises the price
that the homeowners can sell

00:18:44.923 --> 00:18:46.867
their mortgage,
which in turn lowers the

00:18:46.867 --> 00:18:48.960
interest rate that the
homeowners have to pay.

00:18:48.960 --> 00:18:53.931
So again, it's another reason
why this whole operation of

00:18:53.931 --> 00:18:59.078
securitization improved the
welfare of almost everybody.

00:18:59.078 --> 00:19:04.057
So, the pieces gradually got
more complicated So if there was

00:19:04.057 --> 00:19:07.557
default or somebody prepaid,
as we talked about,

00:19:07.557 --> 00:19:10.464
used their option to pay early,
instead of getting the money

00:19:10.464 --> 00:19:13.431
you expected,
you get extra or less money

00:19:13.431 --> 00:19:15.029
than you expected.
 

00:19:15.029 --> 00:19:16.009
That created risk.
 

00:19:16.009 --> 00:19:18.509
And some of these buyers didn't
want to bear the risk.

00:19:18.509 --> 00:19:21.837
So maybe you'd make the pieces
$400 plus the interest rate and

00:19:21.837 --> 00:19:23.528
$400 minus the interest rate.
 

00:19:23.528 --> 00:19:27.242
And leave $200 to what might be
called a residual piece or a

00:19:27.242 --> 00:19:28.880
derivative or something.
 

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:31.440
And that $200 would bear the
risk.

00:19:31.440 --> 00:19:34.191
So if someone defaulted,
you take it out of the $200

00:19:34.191 --> 00:19:36.348
piece and not of the first two
pieces.

00:19:36.348 --> 00:19:39.663
So that split up,
again, made the floater and

00:19:39.663 --> 00:19:43.880
inverse floater safer and
encouraged people to buy it.

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:45.945
But of course,
somebody had to buy the

00:19:45.945 --> 00:19:48.460
residual piece,
which was more complicated.

00:19:48.460 --> 00:19:52.420
So, as I said,
this whole operation was a way

00:19:52.420 --> 00:19:55.118
of accomplishing two things.
 

00:19:55.118 --> 00:19:58.250
It made homeowners able to sell
their promises for more.

00:19:58.250 --> 00:20:00.420
So they effectively were paying
a lower interest rate.

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:03.130
So it made it easier to move
into houses.

00:20:03.130 --> 00:20:05.787
And that's precisely what the
government intended by creating

00:20:05.787 --> 00:20:06.538
these agencies.
 

00:20:06.538 --> 00:20:10.074
It also allowed buyers and
investors to get money in the

00:20:10.074 --> 00:20:13.480
cases they needed it,
in the states they needed it.

00:20:13.480 --> 00:20:15.900
Because the pieces were tailor
made for them.

00:20:15.900 --> 00:20:19.361
So I realized,
while I was there at Kidder

00:20:19.361 --> 00:20:21.452
Peabody,
that this whole multi

00:20:21.452 --> 00:20:24.220
trillion-dollar operation behind
the scenes was,

00:20:24.220 --> 00:20:27.241
as I said, invisible to
everybody and was worth writing

00:20:27.241 --> 00:20:27.690
about.
 

00:20:27.690 --> 00:20:33.152
It was bringing great welfare
gain to the country and nobody

00:20:33.152 --> 00:20:35.190
quite knew about it.
 

00:20:35.190 --> 00:20:38.910
So for me, it crystalized what
the essence of finance is.

00:20:38.910 --> 00:20:41.654
The essence of finance is
you're trying to create

00:20:41.654 --> 00:20:43.761
promises,
the financial system is

00:20:43.761 --> 00:20:47.046
creating promises,
that deliver money to people in

00:20:47.046 --> 00:20:49.619
circumstances or states as I
call it,

00:20:49.619 --> 00:20:51.680
that they really need the money.
 

00:20:51.680 --> 00:20:53.698
But of course,
you have to guarantee that the

00:20:53.698 --> 00:20:55.348
money is going to be paid to
them.

00:20:55.348 --> 00:20:57.838
So in order to do that,
you have to have collateral.

00:20:57.838 --> 00:21:02.209
So this entire system is a way
of creating promises and backing

00:21:02.209 --> 00:21:03.828
them with collateral.
 

00:21:03.828 --> 00:21:05.943
So if you remember,
here are the potential

00:21:05.943 --> 00:21:08.778
promises, and maybe some people
want money down here.

00:21:08.778 --> 00:21:10.695
That's when the interest rates
go up, they're buying the

00:21:10.695 --> 00:21:11.078
floaters.
 

00:21:11.078 --> 00:21:12.888
Way over there,
the money's going down,

00:21:12.888 --> 00:21:15.699
the interest rates are going
down, that's the people who buy

00:21:15.699 --> 00:21:16.890
the inverse floaters.
 

00:21:16.890 --> 00:21:20.190
That's when they're getting
most of their money.

00:21:20.190 --> 00:21:23.115
But these promises,
you have a reason to expect to

00:21:23.115 --> 00:21:26.278
get paid, because they're backed
by the collateral.

00:21:26.278 --> 00:21:28.690
OK, so this is not a very good
picture.

00:21:28.690 --> 00:21:31.863
The houses backed the promises
of the homeowner like in

00:21:31.863 --> 00:21:32.980
Babylonian times.
 

00:21:32.980 --> 00:21:35.588
If the homeowner doesn't pay,
he loses his house.

00:21:35.588 --> 00:21:39.226
Then those mortgages
themselves, those mortgage

00:21:39.226 --> 00:21:44.205
promises, are backing the pools,
which are selling shares to the

00:21:44.205 --> 00:21:45.548
shareholders.
 

00:21:45.548 --> 00:21:49.434
But those shares are backing
the CMOs, which are making more

00:21:49.434 --> 00:21:50.950
complicated promises.
 

00:21:50.950 --> 00:21:53.930
So the collateral you see is
used once by the homes,

00:21:53.930 --> 00:21:56.210
once by the pools,
once for the CMOs.

00:21:56.210 --> 00:21:59.118
And then it will turn out,
as we'll see in a few minutes,

00:21:59.118 --> 00:22:02.440
that the investors who buy are
borrowing money,

00:22:02.440 --> 00:22:05.368
buying on margin,
using the CMO pieces they buy,

00:22:05.368 --> 00:22:07.000
as collateral for their
purchases.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:09.328
So the collateral is being used
and reused.

00:22:09.328 --> 00:22:12.035
And so in fact,
the entire system is stretching

00:22:12.035 --> 00:22:14.798
the available collateral as much
as possible.

00:22:14.798 --> 00:22:17.098
So collateral is a very scarce
resource.

00:22:17.098 --> 00:22:19.519
It's very important to running
a financial system.

00:22:19.519 --> 00:22:22.450
Many developing countries don't
have any collateral.

00:22:22.450 --> 00:22:25.460
And therefore they have a
primitive financial system.

00:22:25.460 --> 00:22:27.561
Here, there's a tremendous
incentive to stretch the

00:22:27.561 --> 00:22:28.950
collateral as much as possible.
 

00:22:28.950 --> 00:22:31.900
You can stretch it by using it
over and over again or by

00:22:31.900 --> 00:22:34.529
letting the same collateral back
many promises.

00:22:34.529 --> 00:22:36.390
We saw both of those,
the tranching,

00:22:36.390 --> 00:22:38.729
the different CMO pieces,
and the pyramiding,

00:22:38.729 --> 00:22:41.598
the using the same collateral
over and over again.

00:22:41.598 --> 00:22:46.518
So I wrote my first paper,
published it,

00:22:46.518 --> 00:22:47.779
in 1997.
 

00:22:47.779 --> 00:22:51.368
I had written it while I was at
Kidder Peabody.

00:22:51.368 --> 00:22:53.730
And one of the questions I
asked was,

00:22:53.730 --> 00:22:56.286
when you take out a loan,
not only what interest rate do

00:22:56.286 --> 00:22:58.767
you have to pay,
but how much collateral do you

00:22:58.767 --> 00:22:59.618
have to put up?
 

00:22:59.618 --> 00:23:02.598
And that was a question that
nobody seemed to have asked

00:23:02.598 --> 00:23:05.200
really before,
in a general equilibrium model.

00:23:05.200 --> 00:23:07.848
So that was my first paper on
the subject.

00:23:07.848 --> 00:23:10.058
I want to get back to Kidder
Peabody.

00:23:10.058 --> 00:23:13.035
Kidder Peabody,
as I said when I started,

00:23:13.035 --> 00:23:16.829
was a sleepy number seven
ranked investment bank.

00:23:16.829 --> 00:23:18.940
Didn't dominate any market.
 

00:23:18.940 --> 00:23:23.368
But it came to completely
dominate the CMO market.

00:23:23.368 --> 00:23:26.439
So this, as I said,
was a multi trillion-dollar

00:23:26.439 --> 00:23:27.038
market.
 

00:23:27.038 --> 00:23:30.452
And if you look at all the
pieces that are being promised

00:23:30.452 --> 00:23:32.987
here,
what Kidder decided to do was,

00:23:32.987 --> 00:23:35.650
things got more and more
complicated,

00:23:35.650 --> 00:23:37.641
there weren't just two pieces,
there weren't just three

00:23:37.641 --> 00:23:39.693
pieces,
there were 90 pieces typically

00:23:39.693 --> 00:23:40.480
at that time.
 

00:23:40.480 --> 00:23:46.299
And so a typical investment
bank that wanted to buy a pool

00:23:46.299 --> 00:23:49.160
and sell these CMO pieces.
 

00:23:49.160 --> 00:23:51.577
Like let's say,
Salomon or First Boston,

00:23:51.577 --> 00:23:54.430
they were the ones who first
did these CMOs.

00:23:54.430 --> 00:23:57.477
They would try to line up 90
buyers and figure out what each

00:23:57.477 --> 00:23:59.130
of the 90 were willing to pay.
 

00:23:59.130 --> 00:24:02.082
And then when they added up the
prices each of the 90 willing to

00:24:02.082 --> 00:24:03.846
pay,
they'd go and if they thought

00:24:03.846 --> 00:24:06.670
the sum of those was bigger than
the price in the pool,

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:08.828
they'd go to the pool and buy
the pool.

00:24:08.828 --> 00:24:11.510
And then immediately make a
profit by selling off the 90

00:24:11.510 --> 00:24:11.950
pieces.
 

00:24:11.950 --> 00:24:16.618
Well, at Kidder,
the head of mortgages,

00:24:16.618 --> 00:24:20.710
who by this time by the way,
was my young little cousin,

00:24:20.710 --> 00:24:27.743
who through hard work had
worked his way up to running the

00:24:27.743 --> 00:24:30.460
small CMO operation.
 

00:24:30.460 --> 00:24:33.023
He got the idea that what
Kidder could do,

00:24:33.023 --> 00:24:35.838
was to find a buyer for the
riskiest piece.

00:24:35.838 --> 00:24:37.516
The one that I've put in
yellow, remember,

00:24:37.516 --> 00:24:38.130
the residual.
 

00:24:38.130 --> 00:24:41.136
Which was maybe called an
inverse IO, it had different

00:24:41.136 --> 00:24:43.009
names, but the riskiest pieces.
 

00:24:43.009 --> 00:24:46.240
Once he found the buyer,
a place to put the riskiest

00:24:46.240 --> 00:24:49.006
piece,
he would borrow the money to

00:24:49.006 --> 00:24:52.544
buy the pass through,
and hold an inventory of all

00:24:52.544 --> 00:24:53.660
the other pieces.
 

00:24:53.660 --> 00:24:56.566
So he knew, that eventually,
we would be able to sell off

00:24:56.566 --> 00:24:57.759
all the other pieces.
 

00:24:57.759 --> 00:25:00.680
And so we had a tremendous
advantage.

00:25:00.680 --> 00:25:03.453
While everyone else was looking
for buyers for 90 pieces,

00:25:03.453 --> 00:25:06.078
we had to find a buyer for one
piece or two pieces.

00:25:06.078 --> 00:25:10.833
So we then had an inventory of
88 pieces, say,

00:25:10.833 --> 00:25:11.890
to sell.
 

00:25:11.890 --> 00:25:14.147
And as we did deal after deal,
that inventory would get bigger

00:25:14.147 --> 00:25:14.630
and bigger.
 

00:25:14.630 --> 00:25:18.127
So our sales force would have a
much easier time selling a

00:25:18.127 --> 00:25:18.618
piece.
 

00:25:18.618 --> 00:25:20.611
We wouldn't have to call
someone up and say,

00:25:20.611 --> 00:25:23.390
do you want piece number four,
that's the one we're trying to

00:25:23.390 --> 00:25:24.269
get you to buy.
 

00:25:24.269 --> 00:25:27.858
We'd call up and say we've got
a huge stock of different kinds

00:25:27.858 --> 00:25:30.858
of pieces, of all kinds,
from all kinds of deals.

00:25:30.858 --> 00:25:32.680
Maybe you're interested in one
of them.

00:25:32.680 --> 00:25:35.172
So it's much easier for a sales
force to sell with that

00:25:35.172 --> 00:25:38.078
situation than it was for the
other investment banks to sell.

00:25:38.078 --> 00:25:40.882
So of course,
we lured away some of the best

00:25:40.882 --> 00:25:41.858
sales people.
 

00:25:41.858 --> 00:25:45.324
So of course,
the down side to all of that is

00:25:45.324 --> 00:25:49.181
we had to be very careful that
the pieces we held,

00:25:49.181 --> 00:25:51.150
we knew how to hedge.
 

00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:53.635
We had to be very careful that
when we held all these pieces,

00:25:53.635 --> 00:25:55.750
between the time we held them
and finally sold them,

00:25:55.750 --> 00:25:57.160
we didn't lose a lot of money.
 

00:25:57.160 --> 00:26:00.464
And sometimes we were the ones
who held the most dangerous

00:26:00.464 --> 00:26:01.220
piece, too.
 

00:26:01.220 --> 00:26:04.563
So we had to figure out what
were going to be the cash flows

00:26:04.563 --> 00:26:06.828
of these pieces and how to model
them.

00:26:06.828 --> 00:26:08.858
And that's what we're going to
mathematically talk about the

00:26:08.858 --> 00:26:09.410
next few days.
 

00:26:09.410 --> 00:26:12.588
But I'm going to give you a
hint of this now.

00:26:12.588 --> 00:26:14.958
So we had to predict,
among other things,

00:26:14.958 --> 00:26:17.088
what the prepayments would be,
OK.

00:26:17.088 --> 00:26:19.722
And so, if you talked to a
macro economist,

00:26:19.722 --> 00:26:22.042
especially in those days,
and you say,

00:26:22.042 --> 00:26:25.430
what do you think is going to
happen in the world?

00:26:25.430 --> 00:26:28.710
They'll usually say,
well I think in the next two

00:26:28.710 --> 00:26:31.534
quarters,
unemployment is going to go up

00:26:31.534 --> 00:26:34.029
half a percent,
and then maybe things are going

00:26:34.029 --> 00:26:38.084
to get better for the next year,
and beyond that it's too hard

00:26:38.084 --> 00:26:38.880
to tell.
 

00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:41.338
So these mortgages are 30-year
mortgages.

00:26:41.338 --> 00:26:43.865
You can't have a prediction
that lasts a year and a half,

00:26:43.865 --> 00:26:45.670
you have to have a 30-year
prediction.

00:26:45.670 --> 00:26:47.789
And the macro economists,
by the way, are typically

00:26:47.789 --> 00:26:48.130
wrong.
 

00:26:48.130 --> 00:26:50.068
Even in their two-month
prediction or six month

00:26:50.068 --> 00:26:50.660
predictions.
 

00:26:50.660 --> 00:26:54.646
So how can we risk billions of
dollars holding an instrument

00:26:54.646 --> 00:26:57.517
that's 30 years long,
which depends on what people

00:26:57.517 --> 00:26:59.298
are going to do over the next 30
years?

00:26:59.298 --> 00:27:02.250
Well the answer is you can't
make a prediction and expect it

00:27:02.250 --> 00:27:02.950
to be right.
 

00:27:02.950 --> 00:27:05.140
But you can make a conditional
prediction.

00:27:05.140 --> 00:27:07.218
You can say,
if interest rates do such and

00:27:07.218 --> 00:27:10.989
such for the next four years,
and housing prices do such and

00:27:10.989 --> 00:27:14.727
such for the next four years,
then in that fifth year,

00:27:14.727 --> 00:27:16.750
pre payments will be so and so.
 

00:27:16.750 --> 00:27:18.848
That's a conditional prediction.
 

00:27:18.848 --> 00:27:21.898
It's much easier to make a
conditional prediction than an

00:27:21.898 --> 00:27:23.368
unconditional prediction.
 

00:27:23.368 --> 00:27:27.685
It's shocking that so many
economists are lured into making

00:27:27.685 --> 00:27:29.769
unconditional predictions.
 

00:27:29.769 --> 00:27:31.528
It's not a business we should
be in.

00:27:31.528 --> 00:27:33.529
We should always be making
conditional predictions.

00:27:33.529 --> 00:27:36.980
Well, I learned that lesson at
Kidder.

00:27:36.980 --> 00:27:38.907
So, you know,
the idea of possible worlds is

00:27:38.907 --> 00:27:41.690
going to play a central role in
our course from here on out.

00:27:41.690 --> 00:27:45.915
And the possible worlds are the
paths of interest rates or home

00:27:45.915 --> 00:27:46.529
prices.
 

00:27:46.529 --> 00:27:50.176
And so here's a very short,
this is maybe a one year into

00:27:50.176 --> 00:27:53.890
the future, and we'd have to go
30 years in the future.

00:27:53.890 --> 00:27:56.768
As you can imagine,
and this is just actually a

00:27:56.768 --> 00:27:59.895
much smaller group of
possibilities than we used to

00:27:59.895 --> 00:28:00.710
consider.
 

00:28:00.710 --> 00:28:03.160
But, you see all the
possibilities that could unfold

00:28:03.160 --> 00:28:04.410
over the next 12 months.
 

00:28:04.410 --> 00:28:08.358
And you see the blue line is
one of those possible paths.

00:28:08.358 --> 00:28:10.790
So we have to predict,
if we knew which path interest

00:28:10.790 --> 00:28:12.990
rates and housing prices were
going to take,

00:28:12.990 --> 00:28:16.220
like that blue line,
could we then predict,

00:28:16.220 --> 00:28:19.210
at the end of the blue line,
what pre payments would be.

00:28:19.210 --> 00:28:21.666
Of course, if you followed
another path down to here,

00:28:21.666 --> 00:28:24.220
we'd make a different
prediction about pre payments.

00:28:24.220 --> 00:28:27.990
So, the cash flows are the pre
payments and defaults.

00:28:27.990 --> 00:28:30.240
That's what we have to predict.
 

00:28:30.240 --> 00:28:34.250
And so, you might say,
what good is it to predict a

00:28:34.250 --> 00:28:37.618
different number on each of
these trees.

00:28:37.618 --> 00:28:39.982
Then basically what you're
saying is you don't know what's

00:28:39.982 --> 00:28:40.730
going to happen.
 

00:28:40.730 --> 00:28:42.390
But that's far from the truth.
 

00:28:42.390 --> 00:28:46.633
If you know what the payments
are on each of the paths and

00:28:46.633 --> 00:28:49.088
then you can hedge those paths.
 

00:28:49.088 --> 00:28:51.222
So for example,
suppose the payments are very

00:28:51.222 --> 00:28:52.970
low here and very high at the
top.

00:28:52.970 --> 00:28:55.753
Well, if you can buy another
instrument that pays you

00:28:55.753 --> 00:28:58.611
something at the bottom,
and you pay at the top,

00:28:58.611 --> 00:29:02.355
you can offset the variation in
cash flows and the mortgage by

00:29:02.355 --> 00:29:05.854
that other instrument and
guarantee yourself the same safe

00:29:05.854 --> 00:29:07.880
payment all the way through.
 

00:29:07.880 --> 00:29:10.164
That's the sort of thing that
we did it at Kidder Peabody,

00:29:10.164 --> 00:29:11.970
which we're going to study in
great detail.

00:29:11.970 --> 00:29:15.080
We held these complicated
pieces whose payments would vary

00:29:15.080 --> 00:29:15.900
tremendously.
 

00:29:15.900 --> 00:29:18.259
So we ran a huge risk of losing
all our money.

00:29:18.259 --> 00:29:20.440
But then we would hedge them
with some other instruments.

00:29:20.440 --> 00:29:23.150
So in the end,
we've got a pretty safe return.

00:29:23.150 --> 00:29:26.003
And because we knew the return
was safe, we felt we could pay

00:29:26.003 --> 00:29:27.670
up a good amount of money for
it.

00:29:27.670 --> 00:29:29.719
Whereas other buyers who
couldn't hedge it,

00:29:29.719 --> 00:29:31.328
wouldn't want to buy it at all.
 

00:29:31.328 --> 00:29:35.759
So, now let's just see how good
the predictions were.

00:29:35.759 --> 00:29:39.009
Here's a typical history of pre
payments.

00:29:39.009 --> 00:29:47.759
So you can see it ranges to 99
from 88, something like that.

00:29:47.759 --> 00:29:50.529
So it's 10 years,
11 years, of pre payments.

00:29:50.529 --> 00:29:54.078
So that's the percentage of
people who prepay every year.

00:29:54.078 --> 00:29:56.078
So it's the annualized
percentage.

00:29:56.078 --> 00:29:58.249
So every month,
you check how many people paid

00:29:58.249 --> 00:30:01.276
off their mortgage early,
and you assume that rate stayed

00:30:01.276 --> 00:30:03.170
the same for the whole 12
months,

00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:05.210
what would the pre payment
percentage be?

00:30:05.210 --> 00:30:07.068
That's what the number measures
all the time.

00:30:07.068 --> 00:30:09.338
You see in some months it's
practically zero.

00:30:09.338 --> 00:30:13.028
These are pre payments for a
mortgage issued in 1986 that had

00:30:13.028 --> 00:30:13.950
an 8% coupon.
 

00:30:13.950 --> 00:30:17.733
So all basically,
1986 mortgages with an 8%

00:30:17.733 --> 00:30:23.318
coupon issued by Fannie Mae or
some big pool of them anyway.

00:30:23.318 --> 00:30:25.667
So you see sometimes the pre
payments are very low,

00:30:25.667 --> 00:30:27.358
sometimes they're incredibly
high.

00:30:27.358 --> 00:30:29.871
How standing at the bottom at
the back there,

00:30:29.871 --> 00:30:33.352
in '88 say, could you possibly
have predicted that pre payment

00:30:33.352 --> 00:30:34.380
going forward?
 

00:30:34.380 --> 00:30:36.480
You know with the ups and downs
and stuff like that.

00:30:36.480 --> 00:30:38.500
Well you couldn't,
if you made it unconditional.

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:40.858
But if you made it conditional,
it's not so hard.

00:30:40.858 --> 00:30:43.546
Because what do you think
happened in '93 that made pre

00:30:43.546 --> 00:30:44.789
payments go up so high?
 

00:30:44.789 --> 00:30:47.348
It was interest rates went down.
 

00:30:47.348 --> 00:30:49.893
Homeowners had an opportunity
to refinance at a lower interest

00:30:49.893 --> 00:30:51.269
rate with a different mortgage.
 

00:30:51.269 --> 00:30:52.380
So of course they did that.
 

00:30:52.380 --> 00:30:55.103
And in those other months,
when pre payments are very low,

00:30:55.103 --> 00:30:56.680
the interest rates were higher.
 

00:30:56.680 --> 00:31:00.817
So clearly, there's a
connection between the mortgage

00:31:00.817 --> 00:31:05.590
rate you got and your original
mortgage and the new rate that

00:31:05.590 --> 00:31:07.740
you can refinance into.
 

00:31:07.740 --> 00:31:10.098
And that is part of your
conditional prediction.

00:31:10.098 --> 00:31:13.440
But another thing that's
interesting is burn out.

00:31:13.440 --> 00:31:18.799
So if you look at two pools,
one issued in '95 and one

00:31:18.799 --> 00:31:22.739
issued in '92,
and with exactly the same

00:31:22.739 --> 00:31:27.890
coupons, you'll see that the
older one is always pre paying

00:31:27.890 --> 00:31:30.108
less than the new one.
 

00:31:30.108 --> 00:31:33.140
At least starting from '95
onward.

00:31:33.140 --> 00:31:37.410
So it's as if the old one burns
out.

00:31:37.410 --> 00:31:40.664
Once it has an opportunity to
pre pay, you see a lot of pre

00:31:40.664 --> 00:31:42.630
payments and then they slow
down.

00:31:42.630 --> 00:31:45.140
So that's another thing people
had observed.

00:31:45.140 --> 00:31:49.117
So you might have thought the
standard way of modeling things

00:31:49.117 --> 00:31:51.970
at that time was to just do a
regression.

00:31:51.970 --> 00:31:55.890
You say, well we figured out
that pre payments depend on the

00:31:55.890 --> 00:31:59.808
new interest rate and how much
more in the money you are.

00:31:59.808 --> 00:32:02.160
And it depends on how long
you've been in the money because

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:02.890
of the burn out.
 

00:32:02.890 --> 00:32:06.180
You try to estimate a curve,
like an S curve or something,

00:32:06.180 --> 00:32:09.354
that depends on parameters,
that's on the interest rate,

00:32:09.354 --> 00:32:10.740
and on the burn out.
 

00:32:10.740 --> 00:32:12.250
How long you've been in the
money.

00:32:12.250 --> 00:32:14.943
And according to some
parameters that described the S

00:32:14.943 --> 00:32:17.118
and you tried estimate those
parameters.

00:32:17.118 --> 00:32:19.096
So that would be an old
fashioned way of measuring

00:32:19.096 --> 00:32:19.460
things.
 

00:32:19.460 --> 00:32:22.229
But as we're going to see in
this course, we look at

00:32:22.229 --> 00:32:24.509
everything from an agent based
approach.

00:32:24.509 --> 00:32:27.318
So what are the individual
agents doing?

00:32:27.318 --> 00:32:31.990
So, I got the idea of trying to
model all you care about is

00:32:31.990 --> 00:32:36.420
aggregate pre payments,
what is the whole pool doing?

00:32:36.420 --> 00:32:38.366
But I decided,
let's try and predict every

00:32:38.366 --> 00:32:39.269
single homeowner.
 

00:32:39.269 --> 00:32:42.188
So let's try to put ourselves
in the mind of every homeowner

00:32:42.188 --> 00:32:43.029
in the country.
 

00:32:43.029 --> 00:32:45.430
Why are they pre paying or not
pre paying?

00:32:45.430 --> 00:32:48.509
Well, they're pre paying if
they get an opportunity to save

00:32:48.509 --> 00:32:49.200
some money.
 

00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:55.038
But, we know from that graph
that lots of people don't

00:32:55.038 --> 00:32:56.029
prepay.
 

00:32:56.029 --> 00:32:59.750
Even when there's a tremendous
opportunity, only 60% percent of

00:32:59.750 --> 00:33:02.390
the people are pre paying in a
whole year.

00:33:02.390 --> 00:33:05.336
So that means the whole year
goes by, and only 60% percent of

00:33:05.336 --> 00:33:06.318
them have prepaid.
 

00:33:06.318 --> 00:33:09.358
So every month,
8% or 10% are pre paying.

00:33:09.358 --> 00:33:12.200
So the other 90% haven't seen
their opportunity.

00:33:12.200 --> 00:33:14.098
They've missed it or they've
waited.

00:33:14.098 --> 00:33:17.200
So clearly, not everybody jumps
at the opportunity.

00:33:17.200 --> 00:33:19.358
So it must be that people are
different somehow.

00:33:19.358 --> 00:33:23.278
Even though they're in exactly
the same circumstance in terms

00:33:23.278 --> 00:33:24.390
of refinancing.
 

00:33:24.390 --> 00:33:27.368
So, you have to account for the
difference.

00:33:27.368 --> 00:33:30.661
So, I imagined that different
people have a different cost of

00:33:30.661 --> 00:33:31.319
prepaying.
 

00:33:31.319 --> 00:33:33.308
It's a hassle to prepay.
 

00:33:33.308 --> 00:33:36.140
Maybe you literally have to pay
some money to prepay.

00:33:36.140 --> 00:33:38.548
Maybe you have to take a day
off from your job.

00:33:38.548 --> 00:33:40.788
Some people have other things
to do.

00:33:40.788 --> 00:33:42.722
They're not that alert because
they're paying attention to

00:33:42.722 --> 00:33:44.588
their kids or they're paying
attention to their work.

00:33:44.588 --> 00:33:46.680
So not everybody has the same
alertness.

00:33:46.680 --> 00:33:49.108
And not everyone follows
financial matters as closely as

00:33:49.108 --> 00:33:49.858
everybody does.
 

00:33:49.858 --> 00:33:52.383
So, also over time,
people are getting more

00:33:52.383 --> 00:33:55.626
rational and beginning to
understand the market and pre

00:33:55.626 --> 00:33:57.130
paying more and more.
 

00:33:57.130 --> 00:33:59.519
And of course,
people hear from their friends.

00:33:59.519 --> 00:34:01.666
If their friends are all
prepaying, it's more likely that

00:34:01.666 --> 00:34:03.470
they'll think about it and
prepay themselves.

00:34:03.470 --> 00:34:07.951
So I built a model,
together with the researchers

00:34:07.951 --> 00:34:09.820
at Kidder Peabody.
 

00:34:09.820 --> 00:34:13.436
And then later we built the
model of pre payments based on

00:34:13.436 --> 00:34:16.420
every individual making a
different decision.

00:34:16.420 --> 00:34:18.677
So an individual is
characterized by his cost and

00:34:18.677 --> 00:34:19.429
his alertness.
 

00:34:19.429 --> 00:34:22.197
So different individuals have
different costs and different

00:34:22.197 --> 00:34:22.768
alertness.
 

00:34:22.768 --> 00:34:25.818
And by watching how they
behave, we can come to guess

00:34:25.818 --> 00:34:29.159
what the cost and alertness is
of each of these people.

00:34:29.159 --> 00:34:33.556
So you see this model captures
all the effects that we talked

00:34:33.556 --> 00:34:34.730
about already.
 

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:39.215
If you have a pool of people,
you can see the vertical is how

00:34:39.215 --> 00:34:41.309
many people of each types.
 

00:34:41.309 --> 00:34:43.880
So there are different costs
and different alertnesses.

00:34:43.880 --> 00:34:46.478
And so at the beginning,
when you have a new pool,

00:34:46.478 --> 00:34:48.969
like on the right,
there are a lot of people.

00:34:48.969 --> 00:34:52.000
And as, they get opportunities
to refinance,

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:55.405
it's not random people who
prepay, it's the people with the

00:34:55.405 --> 00:34:58.400
highest alertness and the lowest
cost who prepay.

00:34:58.400 --> 00:35:00.456
So over time,
as a pool gets older,

00:35:00.456 --> 00:35:03.300
the distribution of people is
going to shift.

00:35:03.300 --> 00:35:07.007
It's going to be have less
hyper alert and low cost people

00:35:07.007 --> 00:35:09.739
and more high cost and low alert
people.

00:35:09.739 --> 00:35:11.750
That's why the pool is going to
slow down.

00:35:11.750 --> 00:35:14.586
So burn out is naturally
explained by an agent based

00:35:14.586 --> 00:35:15.199
approach.
 

00:35:15.199 --> 00:35:18.059
So anyway, as we go through the
course, we're going to emphasize

00:35:18.059 --> 00:35:19.329
this agent based approach.
 

00:35:19.329 --> 00:35:22.554
So building a model like that,
starting in the 1980s,

00:35:22.554 --> 00:35:25.840
and making a conditional
prediction, you can get a fit

00:35:25.840 --> 00:35:27.389
that looks like this.
 

00:35:27.389 --> 00:35:30.099
So notice, you make some
