00:35:39.989 --> 00:35:43.869
OK, so that was my Kidder
Peabody days.

00:35:43.869 --> 00:35:46.335
And I thought,
my gosh, we're doing incredibly

00:35:46.335 --> 00:35:46.719
well.
 

00:35:46.719 --> 00:35:48.780
We're helping the country.
 

00:35:48.780 --> 00:35:52.503
We're doing things in a
colossal scale that nobody had

00:35:52.503 --> 00:35:53.840
ever done before.
 

00:35:53.840 --> 00:35:56.815
I think I may have not
emphasized enough that Kidder

00:35:56.815 --> 00:35:59.090
Peabody came to dominate this
market.

00:35:59.090 --> 00:36:02.730
We controlled over 20% of all
the issuance.

00:36:02.730 --> 00:36:05.125
Remember, there were trillions
of dollars of things being

00:36:05.125 --> 00:36:05.510
issued.
 

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:09.407
So this little group of 20 year
old kids basically,

00:36:09.407 --> 00:36:12.059
plus me the old guy in
research.

00:36:12.059 --> 00:36:14.492
So them, the traders,
they were issuing something on

00:36:14.492 --> 00:36:17.260
the scale of half a trillion to
a trillion dollars of these

00:36:17.260 --> 00:36:17.690
CMOs.
 

00:36:17.690 --> 00:36:22.099
These kids in their mid 20s or
late twenties.

00:36:22.099 --> 00:36:24.679
And the world seemed to be a
better place for it.

00:36:24.679 --> 00:36:26.833
And I thought,
my gosh this is an untold story

00:36:26.833 --> 00:36:27.840
that needs telling.
 

00:36:27.840 --> 00:36:30.110
And it's an incredible success
story.

00:36:30.110 --> 00:36:37.289
Well, things suddenly changed
and in 1994 there was a crash.

00:36:37.289 --> 00:36:39.920
So this is the first of three
crashes I've lived through.

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:42.300
There was a scandal at Kidder
Peabody,

00:36:42.300 --> 00:36:45.280
the Joe Jet scandal,
who was a trader,

00:36:45.280 --> 00:36:49.375
a government bond trader,
who was accused of doctoring

00:36:49.375 --> 00:36:52.389
the books and faking his big
profits.

00:36:52.389 --> 00:36:55.090
He had been Kidder Peabody man
of the year in 1993.

00:36:55.090 --> 00:36:58.126
And then in 1994,
they decided that all his

00:36:58.126 --> 00:37:02.250
profits were fictitious and that
he doctored the books.

00:37:02.250 --> 00:37:03.469
And so he was fired.
 

00:37:03.469 --> 00:37:05.889
But he sued Kidder for
discrimination.

00:37:05.889 --> 00:37:08.300
And it was a tremendous
controversy that was in the

00:37:08.300 --> 00:37:10.518
front pages of the papers for
months on end.

00:37:10.518 --> 00:37:12.657
And finally,
General Electric,

00:37:12.657 --> 00:37:15.900
who owned Kidder Peabody,
closed the firm.

00:37:15.900 --> 00:37:19.358
After hundred 135 five years,
or I guess 129 years,

00:37:19.358 --> 00:37:20.949
they closed the firm.
 

00:37:20.949 --> 00:37:24.900
So I had to go back one day,
from Yale,

00:37:24.900 --> 00:37:27.168
to Kidder Peabody,
and I invited those 75 people

00:37:27.168 --> 00:37:29.340
in the research department into
my office,

00:37:29.340 --> 00:37:31.760
and I said you're fired.
 

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:34.907
And then I got up and I went to
the office next door and

00:37:34.907 --> 00:37:36.969
somebody said to me,
you're fired.

00:37:36.969 --> 00:37:41.090
And so we all fired each other
and the entire 130-year-old

00:37:41.090 --> 00:37:42.969
company came to a close.
 

00:37:42.969 --> 00:37:49.943
So, the head trader of
mortgages and bunch of his top

00:37:49.943 --> 00:37:55.309
lieutenants decided from a hedge
fund.

00:37:55.309 --> 00:37:58.041
So Kidder Peabody got closed,
actually sold,

00:37:58.041 --> 00:38:01.090
it wasn't closed,
it was sold to Paine Webber.

00:38:01.090 --> 00:38:04.347
And Paine Webber dropped the
name Kidder Peabody and hired

00:38:04.347 --> 00:38:06.690
many of the people from Kidder
Peabody.

00:38:06.690 --> 00:38:08.786
And in fact,
the second tier,

00:38:08.786 --> 00:38:12.755
or the more junior group of
mortgage traders at Kidder

00:38:12.755 --> 00:38:14.889
Peabody,
which was the leading mortgage

00:38:14.889 --> 00:38:17.157
company at the time,
they took over the desk at

00:38:17.157 --> 00:38:17.920
Paine Webber.
 

00:38:17.920 --> 00:38:20.190
And then Paine Webber was
bought by UBS.

00:38:20.190 --> 00:38:22.780
And those same guys took over
the desk at UBS.

00:38:22.780 --> 00:38:26.532
So the junior crew at Kidder
Peabody, some of whom were

00:38:26.532 --> 00:38:29.730
Yalies by the way,
ended up running the UBS.

00:38:29.730 --> 00:38:31.730
Or a big part of the UBS
mortgage desk.

00:38:31.730 --> 00:38:34.507
But in any case,
our mortgage traders,

00:38:34.507 --> 00:38:37.960
the head guys,
decided to from a hedge fund.

00:38:37.960 --> 00:38:42.336
Instead of selling,
the CMOs, they would buy the

00:38:42.336 --> 00:38:42.989
CMOs.
 

00:38:42.989 --> 00:38:45.260
And we called it Ellington
Capital Management.

00:38:45.260 --> 00:38:47.260
So I was one of six partners.
 

00:38:47.260 --> 00:38:48.771
I was a small partner,
because again,

00:38:48.771 --> 00:38:49.570
I stayed at Yale.
 

00:38:49.570 --> 00:38:53.909
So this introduces the last
player, the hedge funds.

00:38:53.909 --> 00:38:56.349
So what is a hedge fund?
 

00:38:56.349 --> 00:38:58.329
You heard the name,
I'm sure a thousand times.

00:38:58.329 --> 00:38:59.639
It has a bad name now.
 

00:38:59.639 --> 00:39:03.070
But a hedge fund basically
means four things.

00:39:03.070 --> 00:39:05.670
It means it's someone who
hedges.

00:39:05.670 --> 00:39:09.159
You don't just buy and hold the
thing and hope that the cash

00:39:09.159 --> 00:39:11.641
flows are good,
you try to protect yourself

00:39:11.641 --> 00:39:13.889
against as many risks as
possible.

00:39:13.889 --> 00:39:16.960
Just like I explained,
we were doing at Kidder when we

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:20.030
tried to get the same cash flows
in every scenario.

00:39:20.030 --> 00:39:21.800
And we're going to
mathematically study that in

00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:22.610
remaining lectures.
 

00:39:22.610 --> 00:39:24.755
But you try to hedge,
that's where the name comes

00:39:24.755 --> 00:39:25.070
from.
 

00:39:25.070 --> 00:39:27.750
So you try to offset as many
risks as you can.

00:39:27.750 --> 00:39:29.179
Of course, you still run some
risks.

00:39:29.179 --> 00:39:31.730
But you're offsetting setting
as many as you can.

00:39:31.730 --> 00:39:34.206
The second most important
thing, is most of it's done,

00:39:34.206 --> 00:39:36.777
or a lot of a buying is done,
not most, but a lot of the

00:39:36.777 --> 00:39:38.599
buying is done with borrowed
money.

00:39:38.599 --> 00:39:39.889
That's called leverage.
 

00:39:39.889 --> 00:39:42.418
You don't just take your
investor capital and buy

00:39:42.418 --> 00:39:44.577
something, you take your
investor capital,

00:39:44.577 --> 00:39:47.789
you borrow some extra money,
and then you buy some stuff.

00:39:47.789 --> 00:39:50.827
And the stuff you buy you use
as collateral to guarantee that

00:39:50.827 --> 00:39:53.510
the lenders are going to get
their money paid back.

00:39:53.510 --> 00:39:54.949
So a hedge fund is generally
leveraged.

00:39:54.949 --> 00:39:58.956
The third definition of a hedge
fund, third characteristic,

00:39:58.956 --> 00:40:01.789
is that they're very lightly
regulated.

00:40:01.789 --> 00:40:02.730
So what does that mean?
 

00:40:02.730 --> 00:40:08.867
That means that a broker who
sells something has to make sure

00:40:08.867 --> 00:40:13.880
that the client on behalf of
whom he's buying,

00:40:13.880 --> 00:40:17.313
the broker, the stockbroker,
has to make sure that the

00:40:17.313 --> 00:40:20.360
purchased item is appropriate
for his client.

00:40:20.360 --> 00:40:22.170
We have no such obligations.
 

00:40:22.170 --> 00:40:27.673
We can buy and sell with anyone
we choose on behalf of our

00:40:27.673 --> 00:40:28.639
clients.
 

00:40:28.639 --> 00:40:31.389
But our clients have to be
sophisticated investors.

00:40:31.389 --> 00:40:33.190
We have to vouch that they're
sophisticated.

00:40:33.190 --> 00:40:35.851
If they have enough money,
like say $5 million to invest

00:40:35.851 --> 00:40:37.788
in the hedge fund,
they are by definition

00:40:37.788 --> 00:40:38.659
sophisticated.
 

00:40:38.659 --> 00:40:43.532
And then they don't need to be
protected by having a broker

00:40:43.532 --> 00:40:48.574
who's necessarily watching out
to see whether investments are

00:40:48.574 --> 00:40:49.920
appropriate.
 

00:40:49.920 --> 00:40:52.166
We tell them what we're
investing in and,

00:40:52.166 --> 00:40:55.030
of course, we're obliged to
explain our strategy.

00:40:55.030 --> 00:40:57.420
But once they understand our
strategy,

00:40:57.420 --> 00:41:03.813
we don't have to meet the same
test that a simple broker meets

00:41:03.813 --> 00:41:08.643
on behalf of,
let's say a poor retired

00:41:08.643 --> 00:41:10.219
individual.
 

00:41:10.219 --> 00:41:14.043
So there's less regulation and
the fourth characteristic is

00:41:14.043 --> 00:41:16.880
hedge funds typically charge
higher fees.

00:41:16.880 --> 00:41:18.360
So that's what a hedge fund is.
 

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:21.039
Now, the first hedge fund was
started in the 1940s,

00:41:21.039 --> 00:41:22.969
I believe, by someone named
Jones.

00:41:22.969 --> 00:41:24.949
And he was a stock picker.
 

00:41:24.949 --> 00:41:27.088
And what he did,
is instead of picking let's say

00:41:27.088 --> 00:41:29.552
the best car company,
which he might have thought was

00:41:29.552 --> 00:41:32.840
Ford and leaving it at that,
he would try to hedge his risk.

00:41:32.840 --> 00:41:35.849
So he'd buy Ford,
and he'd short all the other

00:41:35.849 --> 00:41:36.920
car companies.
 

00:41:36.920 --> 00:41:40.309
So effectively,
he wasn't just betting on Ford

00:41:40.309 --> 00:41:41.289
doing well.
 

00:41:41.289 --> 00:41:44.155
Because he could lose if the
whole economy went badly,

00:41:44.155 --> 00:41:46.860
Ford and every other car
company could go badly.

00:41:46.860 --> 00:41:49.659
Instead he was betting that
Ford would do better than the

00:41:49.659 --> 00:41:50.760
other car companies.
 

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:54.210
So he was concentrating his bet
on something he understood more.

00:41:54.210 --> 00:41:55.780
You can't be an expert about
everything.

00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:57.929
Presumably he was an expert
about cars.

00:41:57.929 --> 00:42:00.018
And he knew Ford was better
than General Motors.

00:42:00.018 --> 00:42:01.909
So that was a bet he wanted to
take.

00:42:01.909 --> 00:42:04.652
But he didn't want to take a
bet on the whole economy doing

00:42:04.652 --> 00:42:05.409
well or badly.
 

00:42:05.409 --> 00:42:11.920
So that was the beginning of
the idea of the hedged fund.

00:42:11.920 --> 00:42:16.335
Now there's so many risks that
a car company or any company

00:42:16.335 --> 00:42:16.869
runs.
 

00:42:16.869 --> 00:42:19.289
Does their president know what
he's doing?

00:42:19.289 --> 00:42:21.039
Is Detroit going to be a good
city?

00:42:21.039 --> 00:42:22.768
Is there going to change in
government regulation?

00:42:22.768 --> 00:42:25.119
Is some foreign competitor
going to appear on the scene?

00:42:25.119 --> 00:42:27.360
Is the price of oil suddenly
going to change?

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:30.704
There's so many things they can
go wrong in a company,

00:42:30.704 --> 00:42:32.849
it really is very hard to
hedge.

00:42:32.849 --> 00:42:37.027
So hedging really makes much
more sense when you can make the

00:42:37.027 --> 00:42:38.630
problem mathematical.
 

00:42:38.630 --> 00:42:42.108
Well see, with mortgages it
really is a mathematical problem

00:42:42.108 --> 00:42:43.699
to a much greater extent.
 

00:42:43.699 --> 00:42:45.670
So it makes much more sense to
hedge.

00:42:45.670 --> 00:42:47.972
And I think it makes much more
sense to be a hedge fund if

00:42:47.972 --> 00:42:49.590
you're trading in the mortgage
market.

00:42:49.590 --> 00:42:53.255
Anyway, that's what I found out
when I visited Wall Street in

00:42:53.255 --> 00:42:54.050
those days.
 

00:42:54.050 --> 00:42:55.579
So what did the hedge fund do?
 

00:42:55.579 --> 00:42:59.570
Instead of creating these CMOs,
the hedge fund would buy them.

00:42:59.570 --> 00:43:01.630
And of course,
buy the most complicated one.

00:43:01.630 --> 00:43:04.423
So in effect,
the hedge funds would buy the

00:43:04.423 --> 00:43:07.152
most complicated,
the residual piece we're

00:43:07.152 --> 00:43:09.880
talking about,
and try to hedge that.

00:43:09.880 --> 00:43:11.244
So effectively,
the hedge fund,

00:43:11.244 --> 00:43:13.768
by hedging it,
was really carving out the cash

00:43:13.768 --> 00:43:16.983
flows of that last piece into
complicated ways and selling

00:43:16.983 --> 00:43:19.070
them off to stabilize its
profits.

00:43:19.070 --> 00:43:22.690
So really, the hedge fund
actually was continuing the work

00:43:22.690 --> 00:43:26.121
of the investment bank of
creating more and more pieces

00:43:26.121 --> 00:43:28.409
and trying to allocate the risk.
 

00:43:28.409 --> 00:43:31.539
And so the hedge fund is part
of the entire operation,

00:43:31.539 --> 00:43:36.356
which was making this mortgage
market behind the scenes make

00:43:36.356 --> 00:43:41.010
home ownership so much easier
and reduce people's risk.

00:43:41.010 --> 00:43:51.539
Or so it seemed.
 

00:43:51.539 --> 00:43:53.869
We had a hard time raising
money to begin with.

00:43:53.869 --> 00:43:56.967
Because after all,
Kidder Peabody had just gone

00:43:56.967 --> 00:43:58.179
out of business.
 

00:43:58.179 --> 00:44:02.204
And not only had we gone out of
business, but there was a

00:44:02.204 --> 00:44:04.289
general crisis at the time.
 

00:44:04.289 --> 00:44:06.748
It was not only the trading
scandal of Joe Jett,

00:44:06.748 --> 00:44:09.155
but at the same time,
there was a crisis in the

00:44:09.155 --> 00:44:10.360
derivatives market.
 

00:44:10.360 --> 00:44:13.802
Because all these complicated
pieces that were being created

00:44:13.802 --> 00:44:16.429
where pieces went up and pieces
went down,

00:44:16.429 --> 00:44:18.650
of course if you didn't know
how to hedge your risk,

00:44:18.650 --> 00:44:20.699
you could end up losing a lot
of money.

00:44:20.699 --> 00:44:25.489
So Orange County went bankrupt
in 1994.

00:44:25.489 --> 00:44:27.050
And what did Orange County do?
 

00:44:27.050 --> 00:44:29.268
They bought a bunch of inverse
floaters.

00:44:29.268 --> 00:44:32.275
So when the interest rates were
going down in the early '90s,

00:44:32.275 --> 00:44:34.380
they were making a huge amount
of money.

00:44:34.380 --> 00:44:40.170
And the fellow who ran Orange
County's municipal investments,

00:44:40.170 --> 00:44:44.320
was twice municipal investor of
the year.

00:44:44.320 --> 00:44:46.061
But in 1994,
when everything turned around

00:44:46.061 --> 00:44:48.059
and interest rates skyrocketed
for the year,

00:44:48.059 --> 00:44:50.349
his inverse floaters became
almost worthless,

00:44:50.349 --> 00:44:52.650
and he bankrupted Orange County.
 

00:44:52.650 --> 00:44:56.568
So, it was some of our inverse
floaters that were being bought,

00:44:56.568 --> 00:44:58.969
which helped bankrupt Orange
County.

00:44:58.969 --> 00:45:02.483
Plus Kidder Peabody had just
gone out of business because of

00:45:02.483 --> 00:45:03.139
Joe Jett.
 

00:45:03.139 --> 00:45:08.050
So it was very difficult for
our hedge fund to raise money.

00:45:08.050 --> 00:45:14.510
Our motto was we created the
mess, let us clean it up.

00:45:14.510 --> 00:45:16.530
Nonetheless,
we did raise some money.

00:45:16.530 --> 00:45:19.480
We had an important starting
investment from the Ziff

00:45:19.480 --> 00:45:22.090
Brothers and we had an
incredible boom time.

00:45:22.090 --> 00:45:24.530
We made fantastic returns our
first few years.

00:45:24.530 --> 00:45:26.010
50% returns.
 

00:45:26.010 --> 00:45:31.418
And we grew into the biggest
mortgage hedge fund in the

00:45:31.418 --> 00:45:32.420
country.
 

00:45:32.420 --> 00:45:34.670
And things were booming along.
 

00:45:34.670 --> 00:45:37.404
And then suddenly,
there was another crash in

00:45:37.404 --> 00:45:37.840
1998.
 

00:45:37.840 --> 00:45:40.619
So this was the second crash
that I was exposed to.

00:45:40.619 --> 00:45:43.710
So, what happened in this crash?
 

00:45:43.710 --> 00:45:47.367
Well, as I told you,
we were buying mortgages as the

00:45:47.367 --> 00:45:51.456
hedge fund, buying that residual
piece, and buying it with

00:45:51.456 --> 00:45:52.820
borrowed money.
 

00:45:52.820 --> 00:45:55.626
So we would buy the piece,
let's say for $100,

00:45:55.626 --> 00:45:57.309
by borrowing $80 dollars.
 

00:45:57.309 --> 00:45:59.530
So we'd use $20 dollars of
investor capital,

00:45:59.530 --> 00:46:03.190
we'd borrow the other $80,
we'd buy the piece for $100,

00:46:03.190 --> 00:46:06.710
and then we'd leave the piece
with the lender as collateral.

00:46:06.710 --> 00:46:09.153
So if we didn't pay them back
the $80, the guy could keep our

00:46:09.153 --> 00:46:09.480
piece.
 

00:46:09.480 --> 00:46:12.329
So his $100 piece was
protecting his $80 dollar loan.

00:46:12.329 --> 00:46:16.210
So things were swimming along.
 

00:46:16.210 --> 00:46:18.360
We're going to talk a lot about
leverage later.

00:46:18.360 --> 00:46:21.989
Well, in 1998,
one of the big competitors,

00:46:21.989 --> 00:46:24.018
Long Term Capital,
which was founded,

00:46:24.018 --> 00:46:25.768
as I think I mentioned earlier
in the course,

00:46:25.768 --> 00:46:29.679
by Meriwether,
who was the most important,

00:46:29.679 --> 00:46:33.630
famous, fixed income trader on
Wall Street from Salomon.

00:46:33.630 --> 00:46:37.820
And two Nobel Prize winners,
who I've mentioned many times,

00:46:37.820 --> 00:46:39.199
and you're going to hear about
again,

00:46:39.199 --> 00:46:43.199
Merton and Scholes,
creators, especially Scholes,

00:46:43.199 --> 00:46:46.780
of the Black-Scholes model,
the most important tool on Wall

00:46:46.780 --> 00:46:49.657
Street for managing risk,
as we'll discover in a few

00:46:49.657 --> 00:46:50.099
lectures.
 

00:46:50.099 --> 00:46:51.965
So these guys,
the three of them,

00:46:51.965 --> 00:46:55.172
and nine other partners,
12 of them, created this wildly

00:46:55.172 --> 00:46:56.690
successful hedge fund.
 

00:46:56.690 --> 00:46:58.583
And in 1998,
it suddenly went out of

00:46:58.583 --> 00:46:59.179
business.
 

00:46:59.179 --> 00:47:01.371
And in fact,
the government had to step in

00:47:01.371 --> 00:47:03.349
with all the big investment
banks,

00:47:03.349 --> 00:47:05.039
coordinating the big investment
banks,

00:47:05.039 --> 00:47:08.492
to take it over so the whole
market wouldn't crash down

00:47:08.492 --> 00:47:09.260
around it.
 

00:47:09.260 --> 00:47:12.574
We celebrated the crash of Long
Term Capital,

00:47:12.574 --> 00:47:17.019
figuring that was one of our
big competitors out of business

00:47:17.019 --> 00:47:20.110
and now we would have an easier
time.

00:47:20.110 --> 00:47:24.309
But, I remember thinking at the
time that was a mistake.

00:47:24.309 --> 00:47:26.889
But anyway, a few months later,
we got a margin call.

00:47:26.889 --> 00:47:30.240
So suddenly,
on a Friday morning in October

00:47:30.240 --> 00:47:33.585
of '98,
one of our lenders called us up

00:47:33.585 --> 00:47:36.085
and said,
we think the prices have gone

00:47:36.085 --> 00:47:37.998
down,
it's not $100 anymore,

00:47:37.998 --> 00:47:39.460
it's less than that.
 

00:47:39.460 --> 00:47:44.516
We need X million dollars of
extra margin to put for us to

00:47:44.516 --> 00:47:45.670
contribute.
 

00:47:45.670 --> 00:47:48.193
Because the $100 piece
protecting the $80 loan,

00:47:48.193 --> 00:47:50.882
it was no longer $100 piece,
it was a lower piece,

00:47:50.882 --> 00:47:52.530
so there was less cushion.
 

00:47:52.530 --> 00:47:55.010
We need extra cash to have a
bigger cushion.

00:47:55.010 --> 00:47:58.175
So we said, oh this is crazy,
the prices haven't gone down

00:47:58.175 --> 00:47:59.730
that far, that's not fair.
 

00:47:59.730 --> 00:48:02.516
And they said,
you have until 4 o'clock Friday

00:48:02.516 --> 00:48:04.190
afternoon to pay us back.
 

00:48:04.190 --> 00:48:06.489
And if you don't pay us back,
then on next business day,

00:48:06.489 --> 00:48:08.070
which happened to be Tuesday
morning,

00:48:08.070 --> 00:48:10.090
because it was Columbus Day
holiday on Monday,

00:48:10.090 --> 00:48:13.041
we'll just sell off all your
pieces and pay ourselves back

00:48:13.041 --> 00:48:16.409
out of the proceeds the $80 and
give you whatever is left over.

00:48:16.409 --> 00:48:19.103
Well, we figured what was left
over wasn't going to be very

00:48:19.103 --> 00:48:19.429
much.
 

00:48:19.429 --> 00:48:20.889
Because they only needed their
$80.

00:48:20.889 --> 00:48:22.773
So they didn't have an
incentive to sell for the best

00:48:22.773 --> 00:48:24.005
possible price,
although of course,

00:48:24.005 --> 00:48:26.289
they would tell us they'd sell
for the best possible price.

00:48:26.289 --> 00:48:29.199
They wouldn't and it would be a
fire sale.

00:48:29.199 --> 00:48:32.500
So we didn't know what to do.
 

00:48:32.500 --> 00:48:35.820
And we couldn't raise the money
by 4 o'clock on Friday.

00:48:35.820 --> 00:48:37.079
So we called up Warren Buffett.
 

00:48:37.079 --> 00:48:39.460
We said, well this is so
unfair, they're forcing us to

00:48:39.460 --> 00:48:41.840
sell, there's no reason why we
should have to sell.

00:48:41.840 --> 00:48:43.690
This margin call is not proper.
 

00:48:43.690 --> 00:48:45.130
It's not right.
 

00:48:45.130 --> 00:48:46.829
There's no reason we have to
sell.

00:48:46.829 --> 00:48:49.206
What's going to happen is on
Tuesday we're going to be forced

00:48:49.206 --> 00:48:50.949
to sell all of our bonds at the
same time.

00:48:50.949 --> 00:48:52.849
And they're going to all sell
for like $80 or something.

00:48:52.849 --> 00:48:55.170
It's going to be a terrible
blood bath, a fire sale.

00:48:55.170 --> 00:48:56.989
Prices will go for nothing.
 

00:48:56.989 --> 00:48:58.960
We'll be totally wiped out so
unfairly.

00:48:58.960 --> 00:49:00.929
Why don't you buy our firm.
 

00:49:00.929 --> 00:49:04.070
We'll give you half our firm,
some big percentage of our

00:49:04.070 --> 00:49:04.469
firm.
 

00:49:04.469 --> 00:49:06.170
You just make the margin call
for us.

00:49:06.170 --> 00:49:10.679
And then you could have this
firm with these great bonds.

00:49:10.679 --> 00:49:12.059
It's just a travesty.
 

00:49:12.059 --> 00:49:13.789
And it's going to be such a
good investment for you.

00:49:13.789 --> 00:49:17.128
And you can save us and save
the bonds and stop this

00:49:17.128 --> 00:49:17.849
travesty.
 

00:49:17.849 --> 00:49:19.739
And he said excuse me?
 

00:49:19.739 --> 00:49:20.987
And we said,
well it's unfair,

00:49:20.987 --> 00:49:23.010
they're going to force us to
sell on Tuesday.

00:49:23.010 --> 00:49:25.748
And the bonds will go for
nothing when they are perfectly

00:49:25.748 --> 00:49:26.579
valuable bonds.
 

00:49:26.579 --> 00:49:27.590
And they are going to wipe us
out.

00:49:27.590 --> 00:49:29.784
You can prevent that from
happening and own our great

00:49:29.784 --> 00:49:30.079
firm.
 

00:49:30.079 --> 00:49:31.715
And he said,
hell I think,

00:49:31.715 --> 00:49:34.920
I'll wait for Tuesday and buy
the bonds myself.

00:49:34.920 --> 00:49:38.590
And so Warren Buffett didn't
rescue us.

00:49:38.590 --> 00:49:41.610
And so that Tuesday it looked
like we would go out of

00:49:41.610 --> 00:49:42.250
business.
 

00:49:42.250 --> 00:49:46.637
But over the weekend,
we managed to hold an auction

00:49:46.637 --> 00:49:49.360
and sell the bonds ourselves.
 

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:52.369
So in other classes in
economics, you find out how to

00:49:52.369 --> 00:49:53.469
conduct auctions.
 

00:49:53.469 --> 00:49:55.510
I don't have time to describe
this in great detail.

00:49:55.510 --> 00:49:58.934
But let me just say,
that in a typical auction you

00:49:58.934 --> 00:50:01.730
have to worry about the winners
curse.

00:50:01.730 --> 00:50:04.673
Everybody's thinking,
I'd better not be the highest

00:50:04.673 --> 00:50:07.559
bidder, because that means I
probably overpaid.

00:50:07.559 --> 00:50:10.150
Because those smart guys are
bidding against me.

00:50:10.150 --> 00:50:14.099
So what we did over the weekend
was, we called everybody up and

00:50:14.099 --> 00:50:17.668
we said, we've been forced by a
margin call to sell these

00:50:17.668 --> 00:50:18.369
things.
 

00:50:18.369 --> 00:50:19.909
There's going to be a great
deal for you.

00:50:19.909 --> 00:50:21.974
So why don't you come back from
your vacation,

00:50:21.974 --> 00:50:24.454
one guy came back from
Budapest, one big trader on Wall

00:50:24.454 --> 00:50:24.960
Street.
 

00:50:24.960 --> 00:50:27.909
We got a huge collection of
traders there over the weekend.

00:50:27.909 --> 00:50:29.820
We showed them our bonds so
they could think about it.

00:50:29.820 --> 00:50:32.309
And on Monday we held our
auction.

00:50:32.309 --> 00:50:34.429
We didn't sell everything at
the same time.

00:50:34.429 --> 00:50:36.713
At 12 o'clock,
we sold the first third of our

00:50:36.713 --> 00:50:37.130
bonds.
 

00:50:37.130 --> 00:50:39.079
At 2 o'clock, the second third.
 

00:50:39.079 --> 00:50:42.409
And at 4 o'clock,
the third third.

00:50:42.409 --> 00:50:44.239
Actually, we got a little
behind schedule,

00:50:44.239 --> 00:50:45.309
but that was our plan.
 

00:50:45.309 --> 00:50:47.583
And so what happened was that
at 12 o'clock,

00:50:47.583 --> 00:50:49.170
everybody basically bid $80.
 

00:50:49.170 --> 00:50:53.697
So we said, we're one of the
bidders ourselves,

00:50:53.697 --> 00:50:54.880
of course.
 

00:50:54.880 --> 00:50:57.242
We told everybody,
they all did it by email,

00:50:57.242 --> 00:50:59.880
we emailed everybody back,
you've been outbid.

00:50:59.880 --> 00:51:01.610
Either by someone else or by us.
 

00:51:01.610 --> 00:51:02.449
You've been outbid.
 

00:51:02.449 --> 00:51:03.940
And all these guys,
one from Budapest,

00:51:03.940 --> 00:51:06.820
from all over the world back
there,

00:51:06.820 --> 00:51:08.170
thinking we're going out of
business,

00:51:08.170 --> 00:51:10.289
bidding $80,
they don't get to buy anything.

00:51:10.289 --> 00:51:11.440
So what would they do?
 

00:51:11.440 --> 00:51:13.719
What would they be thinking?
 

00:51:13.719 --> 00:51:16.840
So between 12:00 and 2:00,
we're on the edge of our seats.

00:51:16.840 --> 00:51:17.949
Are they going to bid $80 again?
 

00:51:17.949 --> 00:51:19.380
Which means,
of course, we get nothing.

00:51:19.380 --> 00:51:21.773
Because we just pay back the
loan for $80 and we go out of

00:51:21.773 --> 00:51:23.789
business and our investors go
out of business.

00:51:23.789 --> 00:51:26.440
Or are they going to realize
that they have to bid more in

00:51:26.440 --> 00:51:27.789
order to beat other people.
 

00:51:27.789 --> 00:51:29.590
So we had no idea what was
going to happen.

00:51:29.590 --> 00:51:34.268
But the price was basically $95
a 2 o'clock and $99 at 4

00:51:34.268 --> 00:51:35.119
o'clock.
 

00:51:35.119 --> 00:51:38.559
So we celebrated saving our
firm.

00:51:38.559 --> 00:51:42.556
And it turned out there was
another complication after that,

00:51:42.556 --> 00:51:44.250
which I won't get into.
 

00:51:44.250 --> 00:51:47.789
Which is that the thing had
happened over the holidays.

00:51:47.789 --> 00:51:54.878
And so the next morning,
the buyers didn't get their

00:51:54.878 --> 00:51:55.989
bonds.
 

00:51:55.989 --> 00:51:58.150
Remember, we don't have the
bonds to sell them.

00:51:58.150 --> 00:52:00.300
They're sitting with the person
who lent us the money.

00:52:00.300 --> 00:52:02.820
So it was over a holiday,
and the bonds didn't get

00:52:02.820 --> 00:52:04.260
transferred to the buyers.
 

00:52:04.260 --> 00:52:07.932
And so the prime broker who was
supposed to vouch for all this,

00:52:07.932 --> 00:52:09.768
it was a holiday for him too.
 

00:52:09.768 --> 00:52:11.449
And so the whole thing was a
mess.

00:52:11.449 --> 00:52:13.643
And it's actually quite an
amazing story,

00:52:13.643 --> 00:52:15.510
which I don't have time to
tell.

00:52:15.510 --> 00:52:18.132
But anyway, when the buyers
didn't get their bonds,

00:52:18.132 --> 00:52:21.226
the next morning on Tuesday,
they all got alarmed that maybe

00:52:21.226 --> 00:52:23.010
we didn't even have the bonds.
 

00:52:23.010 --> 00:52:25.559
And so everybody made a margin
call against us.

00:52:25.559 --> 00:52:28.304
And we went from celebrating to
suddenly thinking we're out of

00:52:28.304 --> 00:52:29.070
business again.
 

00:52:29.070 --> 00:52:31.795
But sometimes,
when you're so badly off,

00:52:31.795 --> 00:52:34.590
people realize that they have
to stop.

00:52:34.590 --> 00:52:38.141
And so there was a big
conference call on Wednesday in

00:52:38.141 --> 00:52:40.824
which all of lenders,
the sort of number two people

00:52:40.824 --> 00:52:43.085
at all the big investment banks
got together in the conference

00:52:43.085 --> 00:52:44.543
call,
and they agreed that if they

00:52:44.543 --> 00:52:46.670
all tried to get their money
back at the same time,

00:52:46.670 --> 00:52:47.690
none of them would get it.
 

00:52:47.690 --> 00:52:51.030
And so they waited for us to
gradually work ourselves out of

00:52:51.030 --> 00:52:52.050
the predicament.
 

00:52:52.050 --> 00:52:56.929
So we survived the crash of
1998.

00:52:56.929 --> 00:52:59.420
And then after that,
we had another boom year.

00:52:59.420 --> 00:53:01.840
An incredible year in 1999.
 

00:53:01.840 --> 00:53:10.605
And things kept booming again
for eight years or nine years

00:53:10.605 --> 00:53:12.570
until 2007.
 

00:53:12.570 --> 00:53:15.347
Before, I get to that,
that experience was so seared

00:53:15.347 --> 00:53:17.262
in my mind,
the second crisis,

00:53:17.262 --> 00:53:20.018
the 1998 crisis was so seared
in my mind,

00:53:20.018 --> 00:53:22.809
that I wrote a paper called The
Leverage Cycle.

00:53:22.809 --> 00:53:25.190
In which I said,
what basically happens is

00:53:25.190 --> 00:53:28.559
people borrow a lot of money and
they're very leveraged.

00:53:28.559 --> 00:53:30.699
Then something bad happens in
the economy.

00:53:30.699 --> 00:53:34.070
And the lenders suddenly reduce
the leverage.

00:53:34.070 --> 00:53:36.920
And so the big leveraged
buyers, they go out of business.

00:53:36.920 --> 00:53:40.039
The leverage goes way down.
 

00:53:40.039 --> 00:53:41.829
Lenders will ask for more
collateral.

00:53:41.829 --> 00:53:43.719
And there's also the bad news.
 

00:53:43.719 --> 00:53:46.239
And those three things together
completely crush the market.

00:53:46.239 --> 00:53:48.818
And so lots of people are out
of business and the whole

00:53:48.818 --> 00:53:49.630
thing's a mess.
 

00:53:49.630 --> 00:53:53.469
But then after things settle
down, there's another boom.

00:53:53.469 --> 00:53:56.480
And then it's going to repeat
itself over and over again.

00:53:56.480 --> 00:53:59.949
So that's The Leverage Cycle
story I told in 2003.

00:53:59.949 --> 00:54:02.824
I wrote it right after the
crisis of '98 and I said that

00:54:02.824 --> 00:54:05.079
this crisis,
which in '98 seems to be so

00:54:05.079 --> 00:54:08.400
small, could be repeated on a
much grander scale for the whole

00:54:08.400 --> 00:54:09.000
economy.
 

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:13.869
So we had these boom years,
right after the crisis of '98.

00:54:13.869 --> 00:54:16.550
And then in 2007,2008,
there was another crash.

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:18.239
This time on a grand scale.
 

00:54:18.239 --> 00:54:19.710
But it was exactly the same
kind.

00:54:19.710 --> 00:54:21.985
And the last two lectures of
this course are going to be

00:54:21.985 --> 00:54:23.268
about the most recent crisis.
 

00:54:23.268 --> 00:54:28.599
And so we're going to
mathematically reexamine this

00:54:28.599 --> 00:54:30.199
entire story.
 

00:54:30.199 --> 00:54:33.081
And again, after the 2008
crash, when we almost went out

00:54:33.081 --> 00:54:34.969
of business again,
our hedge fund.

00:54:34.969 --> 00:54:37.699
In 2009, we had the best year
we've ever had.

00:54:37.699 --> 00:54:40.949
Better than all those other
years, even in '95.

00:54:40.949 --> 00:54:46.139
So three times in a row.
 

00:54:46.139 --> 00:54:47.976
There's a crash,
a boom, a crash,

00:54:47.976 --> 00:54:49.469
a boom, a crash,
a boom.

00:54:49.469 --> 00:54:54.210
We made back more money in 2009
than we lost in the crisis of

00:54:54.210 --> 00:54:55.159
2007,2008.
 

00:54:55.159 --> 00:54:59.181
So the course has to end with
an explanation of why these

00:54:59.181 --> 00:55:01.909
cycles happened over and over
again.

00:55:01.909 --> 00:55:02.750
It can't be an accident.
 

00:55:02.750 --> 00:55:05.670
It can't be all my fault that
I've been in three of them.

00:55:05.670 --> 00:55:08.018
There's got to be something
systematic going on.

00:55:08.018 --> 00:55:10.809
And that what I've been writing
about it.

00:55:10.809 --> 00:55:12.239
And how I'll end course.
 

00:55:12.239 --> 00:55:13.525
And by the way,
as you'll see,

00:55:13.525 --> 00:55:16.010
I spent a lot of time talking
to the federal reserve,

00:55:16.010 --> 00:55:18.079
and Bernanke,
and Summers,

00:55:18.079 --> 00:55:22.648
and also with the ECB,
the European Central Bank about

00:55:22.648 --> 00:55:24.260
the leverage cycle.
 

00:55:24.260 --> 00:55:28.711
Which I think is generally
becoming recognized as a central

00:55:28.711 --> 00:55:29.480
problem.
 

00:55:29.480 --> 00:55:34.505
But I want to end this lecture
in the next 15 or so minutes,

00:55:34.505 --> 00:55:39.190
20 minutes, by pointing out one
change in the market.

00:55:39.190 --> 00:55:40.780
The next big change in the
market.

00:55:40.780 --> 00:55:44.389
The next wave of securitization.
 

00:55:44.389 --> 00:55:47.494
So, this is the sub prime
market, which we haven't

00:55:47.494 --> 00:55:48.510
mentioned yet.
 

00:55:48.510 --> 00:55:54.630
And which I will now describe.
 

00:55:54.630 --> 00:56:02.610
OK, so what is the sub prime
mortgage market.

00:56:02.610 --> 00:56:06.518
So I already pointed out that
securitization was a great idea.

00:56:06.518 --> 00:56:11.400
Now it was applied,
remember, to prime mortgages.

00:56:11.400 --> 00:56:14.278
You had to be a very reliable
homeowner to get one of those

00:56:14.278 --> 00:56:15.570
Fannie or Freddie loans.
 

00:56:15.570 --> 00:56:18.559
And because those people were
so reliable,

00:56:18.559 --> 00:56:20.420
although they didn't behave
perfectly rationally,

00:56:20.420 --> 00:56:23.413
you had cost and alertness
issues, they still were very

00:56:23.413 --> 00:56:24.190
predictable.
 

00:56:24.190 --> 00:56:31.550
Well, a combination of things
happened in the late '90s.

00:56:31.550 --> 00:56:34.648
Investors began to get the
idea, this has worked out so

00:56:34.648 --> 00:56:38.204
well, and there's so many people
who don't own homes in America

00:56:38.204 --> 00:56:39.639
because they're poor.
 

00:56:39.639 --> 00:56:43.420
Maybe we can extend home
ownership to still more people.

00:56:43.420 --> 00:56:45.815
Of course, they're going to be
riskier, because they're poorer,

00:56:45.815 --> 00:56:46.860
they have less resources.
 

00:56:46.860 --> 00:56:50.193
But we'll charge them a higher
interest rate and that will

00:56:50.193 --> 00:56:52.239
compensate us for the extra
risk.

00:56:52.239 --> 00:56:56.409
The government also saw this as
a great opportunity to help the

00:56:56.409 --> 00:56:56.880
poor.
 

00:56:56.880 --> 00:56:59.559
So this combination of
investors getting the idea and

00:56:59.559 --> 00:57:01.619
the government wanting to
sponsor it,

00:57:01.619 --> 00:57:03.449
led to the creation of a new
market,

00:57:03.449 --> 00:57:06.034
the sub prime market,
which is what I'm going to

00:57:06.034 --> 00:57:06.860
describe now.
 

00:57:06.860 --> 00:57:09.018
And I'm going to talk about
what went wrong,

00:57:09.018 --> 00:57:11.780
or begin to talk about what
went wrong, but I'm going to

00:57:11.780 --> 00:57:14.090
leave most of it for the last
two classes.

00:57:14.090 --> 00:57:16.717
So as I said,
securitization is so important

00:57:16.717 --> 00:57:18.387
because,
let me remind you,

00:57:18.387 --> 00:57:20.440
typically when a bank makes a
loan,

00:57:20.440 --> 00:57:25.480
the bank finds out a lot about
who it is lending to.

00:57:25.480 --> 00:57:30.268
But the bank is a bunch of
managers and stuff.

00:57:30.268 --> 00:57:34.335
The shareholders of the bank
are the people whose money is at

00:57:34.335 --> 00:57:34.809
risk.
 

00:57:34.809 --> 00:57:37.460
They aren't the ones looking at
the loans.

00:57:37.460 --> 00:57:40.032
So if you're a shareholder,
you own stock in a bank,

00:57:40.032 --> 00:57:42.554
two years later the bank is
going to make a loan to

00:57:42.554 --> 00:57:44.219
somebody, risking your money.
 

00:57:44.219 --> 00:57:47.148
And you've got no idea who the
guy is that the bank is lending

00:57:47.148 --> 00:57:47.389
to.
 

00:57:47.389 --> 00:57:50.456
Or what the characteristics are
of the person who is getting a

00:57:50.456 --> 00:57:50.809
loan.
 

00:57:50.809 --> 00:57:54.110
Think of the securitization
when you're buying a pool.

00:57:54.110 --> 00:57:56.996
When you get this pool,
you could be told what are the

00:57:56.996 --> 00:57:59.829
characteristics of all the
homeowners in the pool.

00:57:59.829 --> 00:58:01.380
It's something very concrete.
 

00:58:01.380 --> 00:58:03.760
A bank lends to homeowners,
it lends to businesses.

00:58:03.760 --> 00:58:05.329
It's doing 6,000 things.
 

00:58:05.329 --> 00:58:08.550
Of course, it's risky to have
bank capital.

00:58:08.550 --> 00:58:10.659
You know, equity,
own shares of the bank.

00:58:10.659 --> 00:58:11.690
Because you don't know what
they're doing.

00:58:11.690 --> 00:58:13.018
And they are doing so many
different things.

00:58:13.018 --> 00:58:16.916
You should feel a lot more
comfortable if where your money

00:58:16.916 --> 00:58:19.309
is going is very well
delineated.

00:58:19.309 --> 00:58:21.239
That's the idea of a
securitization.

00:58:21.239 --> 00:58:27.730
It's very well defined where
the money is going.

00:58:27.730 --> 00:58:30.090
So it makes people more willing
to lend.

00:58:30.090 --> 00:58:33.050
Corporate debt,
that's another way of lending

00:58:33.050 --> 00:58:33.590
money.
 

00:58:33.590 --> 00:58:37.557
But if you own bonds in a firm,
you're not the first person to

00:58:37.557 --> 00:58:38.599
get paid back.
 

00:58:38.599 --> 00:58:41.110
The people lending with
collateral get their money

00:58:41.110 --> 00:58:41.518
first.
 

00:58:41.518 --> 00:58:44.217
And if the firm goes bankrupt,
there is a big court case and

00:58:44.217 --> 00:58:46.320
it takes a long time to get your
money back.

00:58:46.320 --> 00:58:47.809
Not in a securitization.
 

00:58:47.809 --> 00:58:52.367
So there are many ways that a
securitization is more

00:58:52.367 --> 00:58:56.570
attractive than lending money
through a bank.

00:58:56.570 --> 00:58:58.489
And that's the reason for the
securitizations.

00:58:58.489 --> 00:59:01.750
Now here are the current
numbers, the 2007 numbers.

00:59:01.750 --> 00:59:04.750
And there haven't been much
securitizations since then.

00:59:04.750 --> 00:59:08.840
So the agencies are now up to
$4 trillion, Fannie and Freddie.

00:59:08.840 --> 00:59:12.507
Now those jumbo loans I told
you about, the big loans that

00:59:12.507 --> 00:59:15.661
the rich people take out,
remember, which was $0.5

00:59:15.661 --> 00:59:18.429
trillion in 2003,
is now $0.8 trillion.

00:59:18.429 --> 00:59:20.769
But there are two more markets
that have been created.

00:59:20.769 --> 00:59:22.829
There's the Alt-A.
 

00:59:22.829 --> 00:59:25.447
Those are people who don't have
credit ratings good enough to

00:59:25.447 --> 00:59:26.800
get the Fannie Freddie loans.
 

00:59:26.800 --> 00:59:28.260
That's $0.8 trillion.
 

00:59:28.260 --> 00:59:30.349
But they are pretty good credit
ratings.

00:59:30.349 --> 00:59:33.409
And then the sub prime
population, of which there were

00:59:33.409 --> 00:59:35.429
$1 trillion loans issued by
2007.

00:59:35.429 --> 00:59:40.619
That's $1.8 trillion of lesser
credit loans that didn't exist

00:59:40.619 --> 00:59:42.090
at all in 2002.
 

00:59:42.090 --> 00:59:45.099
So you add these numbers up,
4.8,0.8, and 1,

00:59:45.099 --> 00:59:49.440
that's $6.6 and $4 trillion of
unsecuritized the banks are just

00:59:49.440 --> 00:59:50.699
holding loans.
 

00:59:50.699 --> 00:59:53.690
So over $10 trillion of loans
as I said.

00:59:53.690 --> 00:59:55.947
OK, and then you add the
commercials on top of that and

00:59:55.947 --> 00:59:58.500
you're getting very close to the
value of the stock market.

00:59:58.500 --> 01:00:03.659
So all right so we've talked
about this.

01:00:03.659 --> 01:00:15.440
The advantages of securitized
loans.

01:00:15.440 --> 01:00:18.579
All right, so how did the sub
prime market began?

01:00:18.579 --> 01:00:20.789
Well, you had to have a few
legal hurdles.

01:00:20.789 --> 01:00:22.974
The first one,
which some countries haven't

01:00:22.974 --> 01:00:25.730
managed to achieve and some
people now are doubting we

01:00:25.730 --> 01:00:28.568
should've ever done,
is it legal to charge a high

01:00:28.568 --> 01:00:31.590
interest rate to someone just
because they're riskier.

01:00:31.590 --> 01:00:33.010
Is that usury?
 

01:00:33.010 --> 01:00:36.347
Or is that a reasonable return,
because you're making a bigger

01:00:36.347 --> 01:00:36.730
risk?
 

01:00:36.730 --> 01:00:41.000
So, there are anti usury laws
on the books.

01:00:41.000 --> 01:00:44.788
And so in order to make these
loans, they had to become

01:00:44.788 --> 01:00:45.630
legalized.
 

01:00:45.630 --> 01:00:48.717
You had to get congress to pass
a law to say that higher

01:00:48.717 --> 01:00:51.750
interest rate loans for riskier
people is not usury.

01:00:51.750 --> 01:00:55.364
So then, you also had to figure
out the tax treatment,

01:00:55.364 --> 01:00:57.070
which happened in 1986.
 

01:00:57.070 --> 01:01:00.820
And so the first pools were
created in the late '80s,

01:01:00.820 --> 01:01:02.750
the early '90s,
and Kidder Peabody,

01:01:02.750 --> 01:01:06.559
by the way, the firm I worked
for at exactly that time,

01:01:06.559 --> 01:01:11.079
was one of the first creators
of these sub prime like loans.

01:01:11.079 --> 01:01:13.079
So it was very small in the
early days.

01:01:13.079 --> 01:01:14.880
And it worked pretty well in
the early days.

01:01:14.880 --> 01:01:18.074
And, as I said,
by 2007 it had grown to $1

01:01:18.074 --> 01:01:22.750
trillion, 5 million people at an
average loan of $200,000.

01:01:22.750 --> 01:01:28.041
Now, these are people who,
as I said, have bad credit

01:01:28.041 --> 01:01:29.059
ratings.
 

01:01:29.059 --> 01:01:31.500
And so they pay a higher
interest rate.

01:01:31.500 --> 01:01:34.268
Instead of say 6% at the time,
or 5% at the time,

01:01:34.268 --> 01:01:37.730
they might pay 5% or 6% of the
mortgage rate at that time.

01:01:37.730 --> 01:01:40.768
They might pay 8% for the first
two years.

01:01:40.768 --> 01:01:43.300
And then at the end of the
first two years,

01:01:43.300 --> 01:01:45.349
the rate jumps up by another
3%.

01:01:45.349 --> 01:01:46.949
Maybe to LIBOR plus 6%.
 

01:01:46.949 --> 01:01:49.375
LIBOR, remember,
is the inter bank interest

01:01:49.375 --> 01:01:49.780
rate.
 

01:01:49.780 --> 01:01:52.668
So, it's already high,
and then it jumps up after a

01:01:52.668 --> 01:01:53.710
couple of years.
 

01:01:53.710 --> 01:01:57.492
Now, many people have said this
is the kind of predatory

01:01:57.492 --> 01:01:58.179
lending.
 

01:01:58.179 --> 01:02:01.177
That the homeowner is being
lured into taking out a loan,

01:02:01.177 --> 01:02:04.389
not realizing that in a couple
of years, the rate is going to

01:02:04.389 --> 01:02:05.139
go way up.
 

01:02:05.139 --> 01:02:07.400
But actually,
there's some rationale to this.

01:02:07.400 --> 01:02:09.786
It turns out,
that if you've made your

01:02:09.786 --> 01:02:12.561
payments for two or three
consecutive years,

01:02:12.561 --> 01:02:16.690
the market thinks you're not
such a subprime person anymore.

01:02:16.690 --> 01:02:19.594
After all, many subprime
borrower are people who are

01:02:19.594 --> 01:02:20.050
young.
 

01:02:20.050 --> 01:02:22.280
They didn't pay their credit
cards in college.

01:02:22.280 --> 01:02:24.059
Or they defaulted on something.
 

01:02:24.059 --> 01:02:26.510
And once they're married,
have a house,

01:02:26.510 --> 01:02:29.798
have kids, and they pay for
three consecutive years,

01:02:29.798 --> 01:02:32.701
the market figures,
well these people are much

01:02:32.701 --> 01:02:33.539
better.
 

01:02:33.539 --> 01:02:36.878
So we'll give them another
loan, they can refinance into a

01:02:36.878 --> 01:02:38.869
loan with a lower interest rate.
 

01:02:38.869 --> 01:02:40.789
Because they are no longer
considered subprime.

01:02:40.789 --> 01:02:43.659
Maybe they moved to Alt-A or
maybe even into prime.

01:02:43.659 --> 01:02:48.023
So you could count on 70%,
by the end of the third year,

01:02:48.023 --> 01:02:50.800
of people refinancing their
loan.

01:02:50.800 --> 01:02:54.768
During all those years from the
90s and the early 2000s.

01:02:54.768 --> 01:02:57.809
So you'd be left with 30% of
the people who didn't refinance.

01:02:57.809 --> 01:02:59.369
Why didn't they refinance?
 

01:02:59.369 --> 01:03:00.583
Probably because there's
something wrong with them,

01:03:00.583 --> 01:03:01.920
they were missing their loans
[correction: payments].

01:03:01.920 --> 01:03:05.219
They were much riskier than the
original pool to begin with.

01:03:05.219 --> 01:03:06.719
So naturally,
you're going to charge them a

01:03:06.719 --> 01:03:07.539
higher interest rate.
 

01:03:07.539 --> 01:03:10.277
So it's not such a crazy thing
that the interest rate went up

01:03:10.277 --> 01:03:11.099
after two years.
 

01:03:11.099 --> 01:03:13.940
It isn't necessarily a sign of
predatory lending.

01:03:13.940 --> 01:03:16.090
OK, now how do these loans get
started?

01:03:16.090 --> 01:03:17.949
There's somebody called an
originator.

01:03:17.949 --> 01:03:22.367
A broker would find a
homeowner, a subprime homeowner,

01:03:22.367 --> 01:03:26.869
and then go to originator who
would create the deal.

01:03:26.869 --> 01:03:29.559
Now what would the deal be?
 

01:03:29.559 --> 01:03:33.693
The pool would be a bunch of
subprime homeowners and you'd

01:03:33.693 --> 01:03:36.449
have to get some data on the
people.

01:03:36.449 --> 01:03:37.949
You'd have to figure out do
they have a job?

01:03:37.949 --> 01:03:39.070
What's their debt?
 

01:03:39.070 --> 01:03:40.610
What's their income?
 

01:03:40.610 --> 01:03:42.050
Things like that.
 

01:03:42.050 --> 01:03:45.135
And all that would have to be
reported to the potential

01:03:45.135 --> 01:03:45.650
buyers.
 

01:03:45.650 --> 01:03:49.358
So a buyer in the shares of
these subprime pools would get a

01:03:49.358 --> 01:03:49.800
list.
 

01:03:49.800 --> 01:03:50.849
Not by name.
 

01:03:50.849 --> 01:03:52.610
You can't reveal the name of
the homeowners.

01:03:52.610 --> 01:03:54.768
But what the zip code is of
every house.

01:03:54.768 --> 01:03:57.661
And what the basic
qualifications were of the

01:03:57.661 --> 01:03:58.449
homeowner.
 

01:03:58.449 --> 01:03:59.320
Do they have a job?
 

01:03:59.320 --> 01:04:00.949
What's the loan to value on the
loan?

01:04:00.949 --> 01:04:02.719
What's their debt to income
ratio?

01:04:02.719 --> 01:04:03.780
Stuff like that.
 

01:04:03.780 --> 01:04:09.349
Now, the servicer,
who's often the originator.

01:04:09.349 --> 01:04:13.460
Let's say the originator is an
investment bank.

01:04:13.460 --> 01:04:17.489
The servicer might be the same
investment bank or a specialty

01:04:17.489 --> 01:04:18.230
servicer.
 

01:04:18.230 --> 01:04:21.670
What they do is just what the
banks did in the Fannie Freddie

01:04:21.670 --> 01:04:22.130
story.
 

01:04:22.130 --> 01:04:23.840
They're the ones sending the
letters,

01:04:23.840 --> 01:04:26.739
telling people they have to
pay, collecting the money,

01:04:26.739 --> 01:04:29.909
and dividing it up to the
bondholders,

01:04:29.909 --> 01:04:31.820
as we'll describe in a second.
 

01:04:31.820 --> 01:04:37.369
And they have one extra job.
 

01:04:37.369 --> 01:04:40.615
Because they're subprime loans,
you can expect a bigger

01:04:40.615 --> 01:04:42.539
percentage of them to default.
 

01:04:42.539 --> 01:04:45.159
And when people default,
sometimes they can't make the

01:04:45.159 --> 01:04:47.780
payments, they lose their job,
something like that.

01:04:47.780 --> 01:04:51.059
The servicer is given the right
to modify the loan.

01:04:51.059 --> 01:04:53.378
The servicer can say,
OK I understand you can't pay,

01:04:53.378 --> 01:04:55.380
of course you can't pay,
you're out of a job,

01:04:55.380 --> 01:04:56.699
you don't have any money.
 

01:04:56.699 --> 01:04:59.465
There's no point of us throwing
you out of the house right away,

01:04:59.465 --> 01:05:00.869
maybe you'll get the job back.
 

01:05:00.869 --> 01:05:03.880
So we'll work out a deal where
we delay your payments,

01:05:03.880 --> 01:05:06.670
or maybe reduce the payments,
maybe even we reduce the

01:05:06.670 --> 01:05:10.148
principle that you owe,
because in the end that's going

01:05:10.148 --> 01:05:12.599
to make our bondholders more
money.

01:05:12.599 --> 01:05:15.471
So the all the bondholders have
no right to talk to the

01:05:15.471 --> 01:05:16.110
homeowner.
 

01:05:16.110 --> 01:05:17.679
They don't know even though the
homeowner's name.

01:05:17.679 --> 01:05:19.652
But the servicer who is sending
the homeowner letters all the

01:05:19.652 --> 01:05:21.853
time and getting the money,
of course the servicer knows

01:05:21.853 --> 01:05:23.889
the name and has the right to
modify the loan.

01:05:23.889 --> 01:05:26.949
And if the homeowner doesn't
pay and the loan is not

01:05:26.949 --> 01:05:28.543
modified,
because the servicer doesn't

01:05:28.543 --> 01:05:31.773
think it's worth it,
then the servicer can kick the

01:05:31.773 --> 01:05:34.150
homeowner out of his house.
 

01:05:34.150 --> 01:05:38.692
And take the house and sell it
and pay the proceeds to the

01:05:38.692 --> 01:05:39.250
fund.
 

01:05:39.250 --> 01:05:42.547
But there's one extremely
interesting provision that if

01:05:42.547 --> 01:05:45.983
the homeowner is not paying,
during the time the homeowner

01:05:45.983 --> 01:05:48.449
doesn't pay,
the servicer has to make the

01:05:48.449 --> 01:05:52.380
payments for the homeowner into
the trust for the bond holders.

01:05:52.380 --> 01:05:55.710
That's supposed to give the
servicer an incentive to hurry

01:05:55.710 --> 01:05:59.157
up and figure out what to do to
change the loan or throw the

01:05:59.157 --> 01:06:00.210
homeowner out.
 

01:06:00.210 --> 01:06:03.054
And of course,
when the house is finally sold,

01:06:03.054 --> 01:06:06.469
the servicer can recoup his
advance payments out of the

01:06:06.469 --> 01:06:08.050
proceeds of the sale.
 

01:06:08.050 --> 01:06:13.940
And then later,
the rest of the money goes to

01:06:13.940 --> 01:06:16.349
the bondholders.
 

01:06:16.349 --> 01:06:19.257
Now, the rating agencies played
an important role in determining

01:06:19.257 --> 01:06:21.150
the ratings that I'm about to
describe.

01:06:21.150 --> 01:06:23.099
So here's the thing would look.
 

01:06:23.099 --> 01:06:28.077
You have all the homeowners
stuck into a pool,

01:06:28.077 --> 01:06:30.070
all those loans.
 

01:06:30.070 --> 01:06:31.750
I'm going to go for ten more
minutes, by the way.

01:06:31.750 --> 01:06:34.768
You have all these loans stuck
in a pool.

01:06:34.768 --> 01:06:36.797
So the money would be coming
in, the homeowners,

01:06:36.797 --> 01:06:39.387
remember, are paying this high
interest rate because they are

01:06:39.387 --> 01:06:40.380
subprime borrowers.
 

01:06:40.380 --> 01:06:43.110
So there's $100 of loans that
went out.

01:06:43.110 --> 01:06:44.670
Let's say each loans is for
$1.00.

01:06:44.670 --> 01:06:47.889
Where does the originator get
the money to lend to the

01:06:47.889 --> 01:06:48.679
homeowners?
 

01:06:48.679 --> 01:06:51.800
Well, the originator is at the
same time creating the bonds.

01:06:51.800 --> 01:06:55.478
So there'd be AA bonds,
AA, A, BBB, with a bunch of

01:06:55.478 --> 01:06:58.862
minuses too, the over
collateralization and the

01:06:58.862 --> 01:06:59.820
residual.
 

01:06:59.820 --> 01:07:03.159
So you'd create $81 of AAA
bonds.

01:07:03.159 --> 01:07:06.469
These guys would pay that
LIBOR, the inter bank rate,

01:07:06.469 --> 01:07:08.570
which let's say was 5% percent.
 

01:07:08.570 --> 01:07:11.777
Plus a tiny bit,
20 basis points,

01:07:11.777 --> 01:07:12.780
so 5.2%.
 

01:07:12.780 --> 01:07:15.739
The AA would pay a little bit
more than that.

01:07:15.739 --> 01:07:17.659
And the single a little bit
more than.

01:07:17.659 --> 01:07:20.739
That's probably misprint,
that should be LIBOR plus 10.

01:07:20.739 --> 01:07:23.092
LIBOR plus 20,
LIBOR plus 30,

01:07:23.092 --> 01:07:26.119
and then the BBBs,
LIBOR plus 130.

01:07:26.119 --> 01:07:30.940
So you'd issue $81 worth of
triple AAAs, $7 of AAs,

01:07:30.940 --> 01:07:33.159
$5 of As, $5 of BBBs.
 

01:07:33.159 --> 01:07:35.489
That adds up to $88, $93, $98.
 

01:07:35.489 --> 01:07:40.070
You're only getting $98.
 

01:07:40.070 --> 01:07:43.260
So you've got $98 worth of
bonds that you used.

01:07:43.260 --> 01:07:47.139
So the originator has sold
these bonds for $98.

01:07:47.139 --> 01:07:51.039
He's got to lend $100,
so he's $2.00 short so far.

01:07:51.039 --> 01:07:53.637
But you notice that the
interest rate all these

01:07:53.637 --> 01:07:57.139
bondholders are getting is 5%
percent, or a little bit more.

01:07:57.139 --> 01:07:59.050
The homeowners are paying 8%.
 

01:07:59.050 --> 01:08:01.842
So there's extra money coming
in that doesn't have to go to

01:08:01.842 --> 01:08:02.710
the bondholders.
 

01:08:02.710 --> 01:08:06.769
So there's this residual piece
that gets the right to get the

01:08:06.769 --> 01:08:08.530
extra interest payments.
 

01:08:08.530 --> 01:08:11.967
So the originator either holds
residual piece or finds some

01:08:11.967 --> 01:08:15.170
hedge fund and says,
OK, you buy the residual piece.

01:08:15.170 --> 01:08:18.199
And maybe the residual piece is
worth $5.00.

01:08:18.199 --> 01:08:20.368
So $98 plus $5.00 is $103.
 

01:08:20.368 --> 01:08:23.250
So the originator has gotten
$103.

01:08:23.250 --> 01:08:25.894
The broker's fees,
remember the broker had to find

01:08:25.894 --> 01:08:27.460
the homeowners,
gets $2.00.

01:08:27.460 --> 01:08:29.029
So now he's only got $101.
 

01:08:29.029 --> 01:08:31.578
So he lends the $100 and
pockets $1.00.

01:08:31.578 --> 01:08:35.706
So the originator would get 1%
bear no risk for his work in

01:08:35.706 --> 01:08:37.130
creating the deal.
 

01:08:37.130 --> 01:08:41.920
Now, how can these AAA pieces
be rated AAA?

01:08:41.920 --> 01:08:44.390
Now, to be rated AAA mean
there's a one in a hundred

01:08:44.390 --> 01:08:46.960
chance, or something,
that you're going to default.

01:08:46.960 --> 01:08:56.069
So how could that possibly be,
when the loans are so risky?

01:08:56.069 --> 01:09:00.590
Well, what happens if somebody
defaults?

01:09:00.590 --> 01:09:02.229
So this is the calculation.
 

01:09:02.229 --> 01:09:07.100
What happens if somebody
defaults?

01:09:07.100 --> 01:09:10.764
Well, if you haven't paid for
the first 30 days,

01:09:10.764 --> 01:09:12.868
that happens quite often.
 

01:09:12.868 --> 01:09:14.646
But if you go,
60 days without paying,

01:09:14.646 --> 01:09:16.038
nothing bad happens to you.
 

01:09:16.038 --> 01:09:20.521
After 60 days,
you get a letter saying you're

01:09:20.521 --> 01:09:26.430
delinquent and a note is being
made that's going to have an

01:09:26.430 --> 01:09:29.689
impact on your credit score.
 

01:09:29.689 --> 01:09:32.520
So being 60 days delinquent,
seriously delinquent,

01:09:32.520 --> 01:09:34.078
is bad for the homeowner.
 

01:09:34.078 --> 01:09:36.837
After 90 days,
you're considered likely to

01:09:36.837 --> 01:09:37.510
default.
 

01:09:37.510 --> 01:09:39.993
And so you get these very
threatening letters from the

01:09:39.993 --> 01:09:40.510
servicer.
 

01:09:40.510 --> 01:09:42.671
And after 120 days,
the servicer can start to try

01:09:42.671 --> 01:09:44.158
and throw you out of the house.
 

01:09:44.158 --> 01:09:46.056
But to throw you out of the
house, maybe they have to go to

01:09:46.056 --> 01:09:47.658
court, they have to do a whole
bunch of things.

01:09:47.658 --> 01:09:49.920
And so in those days,
it took 18 months,

01:09:49.920 --> 01:09:52.122
14 more months,
after the four already,

01:09:52.122 --> 01:09:53.630
to throw somebody out.
 

01:09:53.630 --> 01:09:56.823
It now, has taken on average,
a couple of years,

01:09:56.823 --> 01:09:57.979
or three years.
 

01:09:57.979 --> 01:10:00.070
It's getting more and more
complicated to throw somebody

01:10:00.070 --> 01:10:00.300
out.
 

01:10:00.300 --> 01:10:01.590
Which we're going to get to in
a minute.

01:10:01.590 --> 01:10:09.510
So you could be thrown out
after say 18 months.

01:10:09.510 --> 01:10:11.988
Now what happens if you're
thrown out of the house.

01:10:11.988 --> 01:10:14.319
Let's say, the house is sold
for $0.80.

01:10:14.319 --> 01:10:20.948
When you originally had a $1.00
loan.

01:10:20.948 --> 01:10:25.051
Well, during the time the guy
hasn't paid for that year and a

01:10:25.051 --> 01:10:29.153
half, if it was an 8% coupon,
that means a year and a half is

01:10:29.153 --> 01:10:29.699
12%.
 

01:10:29.699 --> 01:10:31.538
So $0.12 the guy hasn't paid.
 

01:10:31.538 --> 01:10:33.920
So the servicers had to pay up
the $0.12.

01:10:33.920 --> 01:10:36.500
And then you have to hire a
broker to resell the house.

01:10:36.500 --> 01:10:38.069
That costs six more cents.
 

01:10:38.069 --> 01:10:40.805
And the guy probably didn't
pays taxes for the whole year

01:10:40.805 --> 01:10:41.439
and a half.
 

01:10:41.439 --> 01:10:43.542
So that's another three cents
or so, that you've lost,

01:10:43.542 --> 01:10:44.970
depending on what the tax rate
is.

01:10:44.970 --> 01:10:48.295
So you've lost $0.12 of
servicer advances,

01:10:48.295 --> 01:10:52.188
$0.06 to the broker,
that's $0.18 $0.03 cents for

01:10:52.188 --> 01:10:54.460
the taxes, that's $0.21.
 

01:10:54.460 --> 01:10:56.689
And the house only sold for
$0.80 instead of 100.

01:10:56.689 --> 01:11:00.279
That's $0.41 cents you've
already lost.

01:11:00.279 --> 01:11:02.279
That's a sort good scenario.
 

01:11:02.279 --> 01:11:04.350
You've already lost 40%.
 

01:11:04.350 --> 01:11:09.729
So the bondholders know that
with this scenario they're going

01:11:09.729 --> 01:11:12.779
to lose 40% about of their loan.
 

01:11:12.779 --> 01:11:16.073
Where does that 40% is $0.40
cents, because remember there's

01:11:16.073 --> 01:11:19.368
only $1.00 loan to that guy,
where does that come out of?

01:11:19.368 --> 01:11:24.118
Well, there was this over
collateralization of $2.00.

01:11:24.118 --> 01:11:27.863
This is extra money pouring
into the deal because everyone

01:11:27.863 --> 01:11:30.029
else is paying a higher coupon.
 

01:11:30.029 --> 01:11:35.291
So you take the money out of
this extra cash flow that's

01:11:35.291 --> 01:11:36.439
coming in.
 

01:11:36.439 --> 01:11:38.944
If the default,
the lost $0.40 is more than the

01:11:38.944 --> 01:11:42.212
extra cash flow coming in that
year, then you reduce the over

01:11:42.212 --> 01:11:43.409
collateralization.
 

01:11:43.409 --> 01:11:46.149
There was $2.00 dollars.
 

01:11:46.149 --> 01:11:49.837
These bondholders were only
owed $98 and there's $100 of

01:11:49.837 --> 01:11:51.180
loans outstanding.
 

01:11:51.180 --> 01:11:54.831
So you could lose $2.00 of
loans and still have as much

01:11:54.831 --> 01:11:57.130
loans backing these bondholders.
 

01:11:57.130 --> 01:12:00.823
But once you get to the next
dollar, you're going to take the

01:12:00.823 --> 01:12:02.979
$0.40 first out of the BBB
piece.

01:12:02.979 --> 01:12:06.673
So as more and more houses go
under, you go through the over

01:12:06.673 --> 01:12:09.180
collateralization,
the extra interest.

01:12:09.180 --> 01:12:11.970
Then you start taking things
out of the BBB piece.

01:12:11.970 --> 01:12:14.926
After you wipe that out,
then you go to the A piece,

01:12:14.926 --> 01:12:17.479
and then the AA and finally go
to the AAA.

01:12:17.479 --> 01:12:22.047
So how could you possibly think
those pieces at the top were

01:12:22.047 --> 01:12:22.590
AAAs?
 

01:12:22.590 --> 01:12:25.819
Well because let's do a simple
calculation.

01:12:25.819 --> 01:12:28.560
Actually, they look incredibly
safe when you start to think

01:12:28.560 --> 01:12:29.078
about it.
 

01:12:29.078 --> 01:12:33.976
All this extra interest and the
over collateralization and stuff

01:12:33.976 --> 01:12:37.010
like that it's sort of 8%
protection.

01:12:37.010 --> 01:12:44.399
And on top of that,
you've got the lower pieces

01:12:44.399 --> 01:12:49.220
bearing the original losses.
 

01:12:49.220 --> 01:12:54.090
OK, so even if you expected 40%
percent of the homeowners to

01:12:54.090 --> 01:12:57.640
default, which is an
astronomical figure.

01:12:57.640 --> 01:13:00.076
It was typically,
in the past,

01:13:00.076 --> 01:13:02.260
less than a few percent.
 

01:13:02.260 --> 01:13:04.962
Even if you thought 40$ of the
homeowners would be thrown out

01:13:04.962 --> 01:13:07.654
of their houses,
and 40% of each homeowner was

01:13:07.654 --> 01:13:11.449
going to be lost in the scenario
we just described of the 40%

01:13:11.449 --> 01:13:16.680
loss,
40% times 40% is only 16%.

01:13:16.680 --> 01:13:19.612
But the AAA pieces are
protected by 8% and then are

01:13:19.612 --> 01:13:22.720
protected by another 19%,
because they're only the top

01:13:22.720 --> 01:13:23.189
81%.
 

01:13:23.189 --> 01:13:27.420
So 16% doesn't come anywhere
close to the AAA guys.

01:13:27.420 --> 01:13:30.980
So that, in 2007,
was a horrible scenario to

01:13:30.980 --> 01:13:31.810
imagine.
 

01:13:31.810 --> 01:13:35.319
That 40% of the homeowners,
they are 5 million homeowners.

01:13:35.319 --> 01:13:38.514
That means 2 million people
tossed on to the streets,

01:13:38.514 --> 01:13:42.078
losing 40% of each of the homes
and you don't come close to

01:13:42.078 --> 01:13:43.430
touching the AAAs.
 

01:13:43.430 --> 01:13:48.532
That's why it seemed like they
should be AAAs and so many

01:13:48.532 --> 01:13:51.630
people were willing to buy them.
 

01:13:51.630 --> 01:13:54.439
I've got one more thing to add
to this background piece.

01:13:54.439 --> 01:13:56.630
The credit default swap.
 

01:13:56.630 --> 01:13:59.189
By the way, things are even
rosier than that,

01:13:59.189 --> 01:14:02.237
at least looked at from the
point of view of 2007 Because

01:14:02.237 --> 01:14:05.122
remember,
70% of the people were always

01:14:05.122 --> 01:14:05.970
prepaying.
 

01:14:05.970 --> 01:14:08.319
That means you got 70% of your
money back for sure.

01:14:08.319 --> 01:14:11.975
So you only had 30% of the
people left who could possibly

01:14:11.975 --> 01:14:12.630
default.
 

01:14:12.630 --> 01:14:17.978
So instead of having 40%
default, you'd probably have 40%

01:14:17.978 --> 01:14:19.220
of the 30%.
 

01:14:19.220 --> 01:14:22.797
So you see, you could easily
imagine that your AAAs were

01:14:22.797 --> 01:14:23.970
completely safe.
 

01:14:23.970 --> 01:14:27.204
And so I think the credit
rating agencies didn't do such a

01:14:27.204 --> 01:14:30.100
horrible thing rating these
things as people say.

01:14:30.100 --> 01:14:32.130
But I haven't finished the
story.

01:14:32.130 --> 01:14:33.939
So watch what happens.
 

01:14:33.939 --> 01:14:37.733
So a new invention that
happened in the end of 2005 was

01:14:37.733 --> 01:14:39.560
the credit default swap.
 

01:14:39.560 --> 01:14:42.328
CDS they are called,
which you've heard a lot.

01:14:42.328 --> 01:14:44.340
So what is a credit default
swap?

01:14:44.340 --> 01:14:47.220
It's just insurance on each of
these bonds.

01:14:47.220 --> 01:14:50.738
So a credit default swap on the
BBB would say,

01:14:50.738 --> 01:14:53.680
if there's a dollar of
principal lost,

01:14:53.680 --> 01:14:55.899
because the homeowner's
default, you take the loss out

01:14:55.899 --> 01:14:59.426
of the triple BBB,
you can get insurance on the

01:14:59.426 --> 01:15:00.560
triple BBB.
 

01:15:00.560 --> 01:15:04.770
A CDS just is a promise to pay
a dollar for every dollar that's

01:15:04.770 --> 01:15:06.470
lost in the triple BBB.
 

01:15:06.470 --> 01:15:09.287
And the CDS on the A is a
promise to pay a dollar for

01:15:09.287 --> 01:15:11.239
every dollar that's lost on the
A.

01:15:11.239 --> 01:15:15.090
So that was a huge market.
 

01:15:15.090 --> 01:15:17.310
It suddenly took off in 2005.
 

01:15:17.310 --> 01:15:20.859
And then there was an index
that was created in 2006.

01:15:20.859 --> 01:15:24.319
So these are insurance on
particular deals.

01:15:24.319 --> 01:15:26.042
But if you put all the
insurance together,

01:15:26.042 --> 01:15:28.310
you can make an index of what
the insurance is like.

01:15:28.310 --> 01:15:32.050
And so you can tell how
valuable the bonds are.

01:15:32.050 --> 01:15:34.912
Because if you see that the
insurance premium is changing

01:15:34.912 --> 01:15:37.673
you know that people realize
there's a bigger chance of

01:15:37.673 --> 01:15:38.850
default of the BBB.
 

01:15:38.850 --> 01:15:41.363
So the insurance market,
the index of it,

01:15:41.363 --> 01:15:45.010
is going to tell you a lot of
information about what what's

01:15:45.010 --> 01:15:47.210
going on in the subprime world.
 

01:15:47.210 --> 01:15:51.560
OK, now, I don't have time to
get to these legal issues.

01:15:51.560 --> 01:15:54.550
But I want to add the last fact.
 

01:15:54.550 --> 01:15:58.270
Things seemed to be going so
well in the subprime world from

01:15:58.270 --> 01:16:01.027
the late 80s,
early 90s, all through 2000,

01:16:01.027 --> 01:16:04.648
all through the middle 2000s
that people got more ambitious

01:16:04.648 --> 01:16:05.210
still.
 

01:16:05.210 --> 01:16:06.430
So what did they do?
 

01:16:06.430 --> 01:16:08.050
They created CDOs.
 

01:16:08.050 --> 01:16:11.479
So what are CDOs now?
 

01:16:11.479 --> 01:16:15.090
Remember, we had these loans
that got cut up into bonds.

01:16:15.090 --> 01:16:17.130
There was insurance in the
bonds.

01:16:17.130 --> 01:16:20.960
So people said,
let's take the BBB bonds.

01:16:20.960 --> 01:16:23.252
They're sort of at the bottom,
they're protected a little bit,

01:16:23.252 --> 01:16:24.078
but near the bottom.
 

01:16:24.078 --> 01:16:26.770
Let's cut those up into
different pieces.

01:16:26.770 --> 01:16:30.362
So we take BBB bonds from all
different deals,

01:16:30.362 --> 01:16:34.832
we put those into another pool,
and now we cut those into

01:16:34.832 --> 01:16:36.510
different pieces.
 

01:16:36.510 --> 01:16:40.149
And so you might have a pool
that's from California,

01:16:40.149 --> 01:16:42.788
and a pool that's from Detroit,
and a pool that's from Florida,

01:16:42.788 --> 01:16:44.470
that would just be a horrible
combination,

01:16:44.470 --> 01:16:47.279
or a pool that's from Illinois
and Ohio and stuff like that.

01:16:47.279 --> 01:16:48.569
You put them all together.
 

01:16:48.569 --> 01:16:53.184
And now, somehow the market
decided that we could cut these

01:16:53.184 --> 01:16:56.684
into AAAs, AAs,
and As with the same logic as

01:16:56.684 --> 01:16:57.560
before.
 

01:16:57.560 --> 01:17:01.020
But, this turned out to be
catastrophic.

01:17:01.020 --> 01:17:03.619
In fact, the market went one
step further,

01:17:03.619 --> 01:17:07.362
and not only took the BBBs that
we said before and made them

01:17:07.362 --> 01:17:10.090
collateral for more AAA bonds
and CDOs.

01:17:10.090 --> 01:17:14.265
But then took the As from this,
which came from the BBBs and

01:17:14.265 --> 01:17:17.380
cut those up into more AAAs,
CDO squareds.

01:17:17.380 --> 01:17:22.037
So that was the mortgage
market, the subprime mortgage

01:17:22.037 --> 01:17:22.828
market.
 

01:17:22.828 --> 01:17:27.230
So you see, that there's a
tremendous amount of synthetic

01:17:27.230 --> 01:17:27.859
stuff.
 

01:17:27.859 --> 01:17:31.028
By the way, these insurance
pieces, if you're writing

01:17:31.028 --> 01:17:34.806
insurance, you're promising to
pay basically what the BBBs pay,

01:17:34.806 --> 01:17:36.939
so it's like an artificial BBB.
 

01:17:36.939 --> 01:17:41.332
So they created the synthetic
BBBs and used those to cut up

01:17:41.332 --> 01:17:43.149
too in the CDO market.
 

01:17:43.149 --> 01:17:50.000
OK, so I'm going to stop now
with one final word.

01:17:50.000 --> 01:17:54.877
So the subprime market of $1
trillion, plus the Alt-A market,

01:17:54.877 --> 01:17:58.050
became the new frontier of
mortgages.

01:17:58.050 --> 01:18:00.652
And as I said,
everything went swimmingly in

01:18:00.652 --> 01:18:02.590
the 1990s and the early 2000s.
 

01:18:02.590 --> 01:18:06.238
And then in 2007,
there was a tremendous crash.

01:18:06.238 --> 01:18:10.005
So in January of 2007,
February of 2007,

01:18:10.005 --> 01:18:14.930
the BBB insurance index
plummeted from 100 to 75.

01:18:14.930 --> 01:18:16.775
At that point,
everyone declared,

01:18:16.775 --> 01:18:18.970
oh this is just the subprime
market.

01:18:18.970 --> 01:18:20.630
It's small thing,
don't worry about it.

01:18:20.630 --> 01:18:22.109
Bernanke said there's no
problem.

01:18:22.109 --> 01:18:24.310
The stock market didn't blip at
all.

01:18:24.310 --> 01:18:28.069
It continued on until October
of 2007 when it hit its high.

01:18:28.069 --> 01:18:30.800
The world took notice of the
subprime collapse,

01:18:30.800 --> 01:18:33.038
but everybody said it wouldn't
amount to anything,

01:18:33.038 --> 01:18:35.551
because everybody
underestimated the importance of

01:18:35.551 --> 01:18:36.680
the mortgage market.
 

01:18:36.680 --> 01:18:39.302
So we're going to see in the
last two lectures,

01:18:39.302 --> 01:18:42.269
how this unraveling of the
subprime market led to the

01:18:42.269 --> 01:18:44.380
unraveling of the entire
economy.

01:18:44.380 --> 01:18:47.078
And we're going to show that
everything that I've described,

01:18:47.078 --> 01:18:49.891
although it sounds very much
more complicated with subprimes

01:18:49.891 --> 01:18:52.180
than it did with the prime
mortgages earlier,

01:18:52.180 --> 01:18:57.592
is really when you get down to
it, the same story of leverage

01:18:57.592 --> 01:19:00.210
and crashes and then booms.
 

